      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>1 threads, <a href=/journal2.html?user=53780&start=0>1</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></form><ul>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f1086625213145678041>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=53780&mid=1086625213145678041>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=53780&mid=1086625213145678041>Clan Ater'Mors--the continuing story</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=53780&mid=1086625213145678041#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Jun 7th 12:22 PM 2004</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=53780><span id= >Salura</span></a><br><span id=notbold>20 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [2.73]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Ater’Mors<br>Chapter 1-A Shadow Knight is Born<br><br>Salura awoke one day, unsure of where she was.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sitting up made her head hurt, but as she did so she realized she was in Neriak’s Third Gate.  More specifically she could tell that she was in the Shadow Knight guild hall.<br><br>“Oh good, you’re finally awake.” The Tier’Dal said as he stepped into Salura’s view from behind her.  “I’m sure you have as many questions for me as I do for you.  But let me start first by telling you what I do know so far.” the Dark Elf said as he drew up a chair to Salura’s bedside.  “You were found unconscious in Neklutos Forest by one of the Indigo Brotherhood patrols yesterday.  You weren’t hurt, but it’s apparent that you suffered a magical attack of some sort.  You were brought to be treated by the clerics and then brought here.  That’s what I know.  Now, can you tell me your name?”<br><br>Salura almost laughed at the absurdity of the question, and she opened her mouth to begin to answer it and realized she had to search her memory hard.  “My name.  I should know it.  I know I know it.  Why can’t I remember?<br><br>“It may be part of the magical attack I was telling you about.  What can you tell me about yourself?<br><br>Salura took in a deep breath, concentrating hard on memories that eluded her.  “I lived in Neklutos Forest, with my family, my mother, father, brothers and sisters.”  Tears welled up in Salura’s eyes as she tried to remember more but couldn’t.<br><br>“Don’t worry, the memories will come back.  This type of magic induced memory loss usually isn’t permanent.  It may take some time to get all your memories back, and some memories may be lost forever.”  <br><br>The Dark Elf shifted nervously in his chair “This is awkward for me, but let me introduce myself, I’m Ulraz S`Lon.  I’m one of the Shadow Knight Guild Masters.”  Ulraz sighed as he gathered his thoughts. “When you were brought in, the clerics treated you and then called for me.  It seems by the items in your possession that you are a Shadow Knight, well more correctly that you have chosen to be a Shadow Knight and not yet acted upon it.  I’m here to help get you started again.  What a glorious career path you’ve chosen for yourself, to serve the God Innoruuk as one of his evil knights, striking fear into the hearts of all Norrathians and repaying the light-lovers for their centuries of weaknesses.  When you’re feeling better, come to the guild hall and turn in your note.  How does that sound?”<br><br>Salura furrowed her brow as she considered the implications of what Ulraz said.  To be a Shadow Knight in Innoruuk’s service.  A life away from Neriak adventuring, sleeping out of doors, and of battle.<br><br>“You seem reluctant.  Why?”  Said Ulraz.<br><br>“I don’t know who I am, how I got here, and you want me to commit to a career?  I need to think about it before I make any life decisions.” Salura said as she curled into bed to go back to sleep, not because she was sleepy, but wanted to be alone to think.<br><br>“Understandable.  There’s one last thing I need to tell you and it’s the hardest.” Ulraz drew in a deep breath and his eyes became downcast and solemn.  “I know more about you than I’ve said so far.  Try to understand, I wanted to know how much you knew before telling you all I know.  In time, you’ll remember and know all I’m about to say is true.  Until then you have to choose whether to believe me or not.”<br><br>Salura sat back up, listening intently to Ulraz.  She could feel her heart pounding already.<br><br>“You are Salura, daughter of Salut the necromancer and Rana the cleric.  You are a twin, your brother is Salur.  You have four other siblings, Noril, Damdara, Gospasha, and Hobbe.  You and Salur are the oldest; you are older than Salur by mere minutes, being twins.  Your family’s home is in Neklutos Forest…”<br><br>“Well then Ulraz, go fetch my family” Salura interrupted “and have them come take me home, or better yet, give me a map and I’ll go home myself.  Since my mother is a cleric, I’m sure I’ll be in the best of hands.”<br><br>“It’s not as easy as that Salura, I wish it was.  This is the part I dread.  Your parents are dead.  We can’t find any trace of your siblings anywhere.”<br><br>Salura’s heart sank.  No memory, no family.  “What happened?” she gasped.<br><br>“The Indigo Brotherhood reports that, in the middle of the night, while you and your family slept, you were attacked.  Your parents killed.  We don’t know what happened to your siblings.  You were found, as I said, unconscious in the Forest.  Apparently from a magical attack.”<br><br>Hatred welled up from within here.  Her ears burned hot and she could taste blood.  “Dead.  Who?!”  Was all Salura could muster through her hate.<br><br>“Erudites.” Ulraz hissed between his teeth as his eyes burned with hate.  “I’ve got to get back to the guild.  We won’t let them get away with this.  Tomorrow I’m dispatching a force to raid their homeland of Erudin.  Blood will be shed in your parent’s names.  I promise you that.” Ulraz stood and opened the door to leave.<br><br>“Ulraz…” Salura called to him just as he was about to close the door behind him.  Ulraz poked his head back inside the room.  “After I turn in my note tomorrow, would I be able to accompany that force to Erudin?”<br><br>“So you’ve decided to be a Shadow Knight?  Unfortunately, the way to Erudin is dangerous, and the battle will be bloody for both sides.  You are too inexperienced to go.  But start your training tomorrow, and soon you can exact your own revenge.” Ulraz slipped back out the door, closing it after.  Salura could here his footsteps echo along the stone hall as he headed back to the guild room.<br><br>Salura tried to sleep, but it eluded her.  She couldn’t get the news of her parent’ deaths out of her mind, but couldn’t remember any of it.  She tried to picture the faces of her family and remembered nothing.  He strained to remember anything prior to her waking up this horrible day.  Still no memories.<br><br>The town crier heralded the start of the new day.  A proclamation was read, summoning all the Tier’Dal forces to prepare to journey to Erudin for battle.  Salura noticed that no mention of her or her family was made.<br><br>Salura got up and put on her tunic, strapped on her short sword and put her rations and water skein in the pockets.  She looked at her pitiful reflection in the mirror.  “A lousy tunic and a dull short sword is all I have to my name.  Some Shadow Knight” she told her reflection sarcastically.  Then as she gazed at here reflection, she could have swore her eyes turned from a blue color to blood red.  “I don’t even know what color my own eyes are.”<br><br>Salura visited the Shadow Knight Guild hall but Ulraz wasn’t there.  She turned in her note to another guild master, not even bothering to get his name.  He gave her a better tunic and wished her well.<br><br>Salura wandered around the halls of Neriak, home of the Tier’Dal, the Dark Elves, also known as the Drow.  Salura spent hours walking aimlessly.  She checked out all the vendors, not because she had money to buy anything, but out of curiosity.  It was like she was seeing the world through new eyes.  She talked to every resident she could find, and tried to piece together as much as she could of her life and the world she lived in from their tales.<br><br>She inquired about her family, mostly about her siblings.  No one knew her, her parents or her siblings.  Many other residents had other tasks or quests to offer to the young Shadow Knight, but Salura wasn’t interested.  It was as if no one from her family ventured into Neriak before.  Salura wandered out into Neklutos forest.  Sensing the dangers that lurked in the darkness Salura drew her sword and examined the area.  She could hear the calls of others hunting in the forest and decided to head to the place people were calling the “Noob log.”<br><br>The Noob log was a great place to learn to hunt; many fire beetles and decaying skeletons wandered past the area and were relatively easy kills.  With each kill, she could feel her skills grow with experience.  <br> <br>Chapter 2-Adopted<br><br>After many days of hunting at the Noob Log, returning to Neriak to sell the various loot scrounged from the corpses of her prey; buying supplies and armor upgrades from the merchants; and training from the Shadow Knight Guild masters; Salura grew more powerful and was looking to attaining her 9th level of experience, enough for her to be worthy of learning Shadow Knight spells.<br><br>Salura had been told by other adventurers that selling bone chips, bat wings, and snake scales to other adventures was far more lucrative than selling them to the merchants.  So Salura collected many stacks of these items in her packs, occasionally selling them to other more experienced adventurers that came through Neklutos Forest.<br><br>Salura was hunting much like she had done for the many days previous when a Shadow Knight of the 20th season or more addressed the zone looking for someone to buy bone chips from.  Salura hailed the shadow knight and offered her stacks of bone chips for sale to Cymbaline the Shadow Knight and remarked on how she too, was a shadow Tier’Dal Knight, but was still very inexperienced.<br><br>Cymbaline agreed to buy Salura’s collection of bone chips without haggling and when Salura held out her items for Cymbaline, he not only paid her the agreed amount, but passed to her a pack.  Cymbaline headed off as Salura rummaged through the pack given to her.  Inside were some bronze armor and a few other items that she could either use or sell.  Thinking Cymbaline had made a mistake, she contacted him, using the telepathy that all Norrathian adventurers seem to acquire after choosing their career path, to let him know she had his gear and would hold it until he could return to get it.<br><br>“No Hun, that stuff is for you.  I don’t need them and although I could sell them for the money, you looked like the type that could put them to good use.  Enjoy fellow SK!” Cymbaline replied back.<br><br>“Thank you m’lord for the generous gift.  I will put them to good use.  They are by far a lot better than the patchwork armor I’m wearing now.”<br><br>“Patchwork armor is for druids.  When you can, buy yourself some real armor.” Cymbaline jokingly replied.<br><br>“I’m saving up for my first level of spells.  I’ve checked the merchants and they cost more than I hope to make killing spiders and skeletons.  Never mind being able to afford armor upgrades.  How did you get the armor you’re wearing now?” Salura replied.<br><br>“When you get older, you’ll kill mobs that drop better loot, like some of the things I gave you and the armor I’m wearing.  It’s not all bone chips and eyeballs you know.”<br><br>“Yeah, it just seems that I’ll never get there.  If two spiders gang up and jump me I’m doomed.  I’ll never avenge my family this way.” Salura sighed.<br><br>“What’s this about avenging your family?” Cymbaline inquired.<br><br>Salura told Cymbaline all she knew about the Erudites and her family and how she will one day make the Erudites pay for what they did.<br><br>“So you’re an orphan?  No family?  No guild?” Cymbaline inquired.<br><br>“I’m a member of the Shadow Knight guild, but I have no family I know of.  I’m looking for word about my siblings, but I think they are dead.  No one knows anything about them.”<br><br>“I’m not talking about the Shadow Knight guild.  I’m talking about a real guild.  A group of adventurers like a family.  I’m in the Band of the Black Hand.  You should consider joining it.”  Cymbaline informed Salura.<br><br>“How?  Do you think they’ll have me?  What do I do?” Salura inquired.<br><br>“To start, you can follow me, I happen to be an officer of the guild.  You’ve shown me that you are what we’re looking for.  You’re not a beggar, or whiny type.  And someday, who knows, you may become a great and powerful Shadow Knight.”  Cymbaline added encouragingly.<br><br>Salura followed Cymbaline back to Neriak Commons where he made a trip to the bank and equipped Salura with more items from his vault.<br><br>“Thanks for all the gear!  I really look like a shadow knight now!” Salura said as she giddily put on her new equipment and tested the balance of the weapons. “There’s no way I can ever repay your generosity except to say that if ever you need ANYTHING, I’m at your service and in your debt.”<br><br>“Never mind that.  I’m sure you’ll make good on it.  Besides, it was just taking up space in my vault.  Now, follow me, I’ve got some people I want you to meet.”<br><br>Together they went back out into Neklutos forest, but father south into that zone than Salura had ever adventured before.  The creatures Salura saw on the way were much fiercer than what she could handle alone and she was glad for the company of the Elder SK.<br><br>Cymbaline stopped and sat in a clearing without saying a word.  Nervously Salura sat beside him, constantly scanning the forest for approaching threats.<br><br>“You’re like my fairy god-father or something” Salura nervously joked.  “You show up out of nowhere, give me these great gifts and take care of me.”<br><br>“Yeah, something like that.” Cymbaline smiled back.  “When we get done here, I want you to show me what you’ve learned so far.  I’m going to take you to an old favorite hunting spot.”<br><br>Out of what seemed to be thin air, a figure stepped into view.  Cymbaline stood up and strode over to great the shadowy figure.  Salura stayed put, waiting for a signal from Cymbaline.<br><br>The Rogue met Cymbaline in the clearing, stepping out of the shadows it was apparent the rogue was a Tier’Dal female, and of the Rogue profession.  Cymbaline spoke to the rogue in low whispered tones, occasionally nodding in Salura’s direction.  It was obvious that Cymbaline was telling the Rogue about Salura.<br><br>Cymbaline turned and wave for Salura to join in the conversation.  The Rogue was quite beautiful, her dark cloak really brought out her soft, dark features.  She spoke with a soft, gentle pattern in a quiet voice as her eyes constantly scanned the forest for trouble.  Cymbaline also was scanning the forest, but more casually, letting his hand rest on the hilt of his two-handed sword as it rested in its scabbard.<br><br>The rogue introduced herself as Crista Ater’Mors, a member also of the Band of the Black Hand.  She had come because she had heard through other guild members about Salura and wanted to meet the young Shadow Knight that Cymbaline was taking under his wing.<br><br>“So young one, do you have a surname?”  Crista inquired as she looked Salura over.  Usually Salura would be bothered by this kind of attention, but the rogue’s manner made Salura feel at ease.<br><br>“Mind if I take a closer look at your equipment dear?” Crista inquired.  Salura just shrugged her shoulders and held her arms out, inviting Crista to closely examine the equipment.  “I may have a few items you could use.  I’ll check my vault and let you know.  Good luck meeting Zanthor.  Cym honey, I’ve got to go.  I’ll chat with you later.”  And with that, the rogue stepped nimbly into the shadows and was gone without a sound or a trace of her presence.<br><br>“What did you think of Crista?” Cymbaline asked.<br><br>“She’s seemed nice.  I don’t know too many rogues personally.  She seems very talented.”  <br><br>“That’s my fiancé. Crista wanted to meet you, to check you out.” Cymbaline chuckled. <br><br>Salura felt completely embarrassed, but before she could do more that look embarrassed, an Ogre came into view in the clearing.  This Ogre was completely at ease in the forest and Salura could tell she was about to meet another Shadow Knight as the Ogre’s bumbling skeleton pet soon followed after, along with several undead skeleton buddies of his he had managed to aggravate along the way.<br><br>“Stupid pet!  Pet attack! A hand here Cym will ya?” the Ogre called out to Cymbaline who had already unsheathed his blade and was tearing into the nearest skeleton.<br><br>Instinctively, Salura drew her own blade and realized that this would be the first time she wielded it in combat since Cym gave it to her earlier that day.  She hoped she didn’t embarrass herself too badly in front of her new benefactor.<br><br>The three shadow knights quickly dispatched the skeletons, but Salura was pretty badly injured.  Cymbaline helped Salura bind her wounds while the Ogre looted the corpses.<br><br>“So this is the recruit you were telling us about?  She’s kind of young.  But she handled herself pretty well against those couple skeletons.  Of course, she needs better armor and weapons.”  The ogre rambled off to Cymbaline, oblivious that Salura was standing right there.<br><br>“Zanthor, meet Salura.  Salura, this is the guy I wanted you to meet.  He’s the guild leader.” Cymbaline then leaned over and whispered “Don’t say anything dumb.”  Salura couldn’t for her life think of why Cymbaline would think she would say anything at all to this rude ogre.  All she could do was nod an acknowledgement to Cymbaline.<br><br>“So what’s your story young one?  But be brief, I’ve got a boat to catch and Cymbaline here has to come with me.”<br><br>“I’m an orphaned shadow knight looking for a guild.  Cymbaline has told me of the Band, and I would like to apply for membership.  The rest is not important.” Salura quickly responded, trying to look formidable to the ogre who was easily three times her size.<br><br>“Fair enough.  We’ll have ya, based mostly on Cym’s fondness of ya.  Welcome to the guild.  Cymbaline and Crista will mentor you; make sure you learn the ins and outs of the guild.” No sooner that Zanthor spoke the words, Salura’s mind picked up the telepathic channel of guild members bidding her welcome.  Dozens of voices cheered for her and wished her well.<br><br>Salura followed Cymbaline and Zanthor for a bit until Cymbaline pointed out an Elvin graveyard, haunted with skeletons.<br><br>“Hunt here.  When you are too experienced to learn anything more, tell me and I’ll let you know where to hunt next.  Watch out, sometimes zombies and mummies show up here, and they can be a bit tougher.  I’m going to help Zanthor out in Lower Guk.  With any luck, when I get back, I’ll have some more gear for you.  Tonight, Christa has invited you to our home.  When’s the last time you had a home-cooked meal instead of one of those iron rations and stale water?”<br><br>Salura shrugged because she couldn’t remember ever easting anything except for rations and the original biscuits and milk she’d gotten back in Neriak.  Bidding her new friends farewell, Salura set about hunting the graveyard.  <br><br>No matter how long she hunted, the stream of undead never ceased.  Occasionally, a member of the Band would stop by to meet her and wish her well.  By nightfall Salura had made several trips back and forth between the camp and Neriak to sell what she looted.  <br><br>Cymbaline’s home was a modest but comfortable home.  It was obvious that the couple never spent much time here from its modest furnishings with its layer of dust.  Crista was an excellent cook.  They ate rabbit stew and passed around several bottles of Elvin wine.  Salura, never before being able to afford it, had never drunk alcohol, got very tipsy and soon fell asleep right at the table.<br><br>When she awoke she was on a cot, covered with heavy, warm bearskins.  Cym and Crista were at the far end of the cottage talking quietly by the fire.<br><br>“A rough life that one has had.  She’s gotten to the seventh level of her training all alone, and with no more than a dull short sword and those cheap tunics the SK guild tosses at you when you sell your soul to them.”  Cymbaline murmured.<br><br>“She seems to be rather intelligent, and I like her sense of humor.  So far the entire guild is impressed by her.  She’ll make a fine addition to the family.” Crista chatted as she tended to the fire.<br><br>“So we tell her in the morning then?  She’s got a long way to go before she can use the name.  And with her good looks and charm, it may not be that she needs a name long.  I hear Maut was to her camp earlier.  He went there invisible; I don’t think Salura noticed she was being watched by so many.  She was very intent on the hunt.”<br><br>“Maut, huh?  That playboy.  Be sure you make the proper introductions.”<br><br>Cymbaline and Crista continued to talk about other issues and as interested as Salura was, fatigue overtook her and she slept like the dead.  When she awoke, Crista had already gone, but had left enough rabbit stew for breakfast with leftovers for Salura’s pack.<br><br>“Head back to the graveyard to hunt when you’re ready.  I’m off to see about a particularly elusive mob, err that’s what we adventurers call our prey, in Lower Guk again.  I’ll come by later and see how you’re doing.”<br><br>Salura ate, and equipped herself for a days hunt.  It wasn’t until she had gotten to the graveyard that she remembered Crista and Cymbaline’s discussion by the fire.  It would have to wait until later she thought “I don’t want them to know I was listening in on their conversations last night.”<br><br>Salura began hunting and a short time later was joined by a young necromancer named Crayne.  Together they killed hundreds of skeletons and had to make several trips to sell their items to the Neriak Merchants.<br><br>“Hey, this is getting too easy.  Let’s go someplace harder.” Crayne said to Salura as he smoothed the folds of his robe.<br><br>“Easy for you.  You sit there and send your pet in to do all the work while you put your nose in your spell book.  Oh, and let’s not forget the occasional time you have to stand up and wave your arms around to cast a spell.  You try smacking these mobs and taking their blows and tell me it’s easy.”  Salura panted.<br><br>“I meant we can get more experience if we go after mobs that are harder, like the ones in the next zone.  In the East Commonlands we can hunt bear, wolves, giant spiders and pumas.  They drop better selling loot too.  We can make ourselves rich hunting there.  These skeletons and their rusty weapons are getting boring.” Crayne said as he dismissed his skeleton pet back to wherever those poor undead souls remain when they aren’t serving their Necromancer or Shadow Knight Masters.<br><br>Intrigued by the new zone, Salura went with Crayne to the East Commonlands.  Upon entering the area Salura was greeted by the blows of Sergeant Slate, a human soldier.  When Salura awoke back in Neriak Crayne told her “Sorry, forgot to warn you about him.  Some idiot was running from him and brought him to the zone line. I’m here at your corpse.  Good thing we’re immortal, huh?”<br><br>Salura made her way back to the East Commonlands and after looting her own corpse prepared for battle.  They hunted many giant spiders and bears, lions and other assorted wildlife, splitting the loot between them as they went. <br><br>The hair on the back of Salura’s neck stood up, she was being watched.  Casually as she hunted she looked to see if she could spot the watcher.  “Crayne cast a spell so I can see invisible people.  I think we’re being watched.”  Crayne sat and reviewed his spell book, committing the spell to memory, stood up and began casting.  Salura’s eyes began to tingle and a shadowy figure became visible not to far off.  A Drow clad in leather, sitting a few meters away.  And yes, he was watching her and Crayne.  “Don’t look, but we are being watched by that Drow over there.  I wonder what he wants?”<br><br>“I see him.  I consider him to be able to kill us both if he wanted.  So why would a person of his experience want here, or with us?” Crayne nonchalantly said as he flipped through the pages of his spell book.<br><br>“One way to find out.” Salura whispered as she strode over to where the Drow was sitting.  “Hail!” Salura said to the Drow.<br><br>“Hail, Salura!  Well met.” Said the startled Drow, realizing that he’d been discovered.  “I’m Maut Trueguide, a friend of Cymbaline, and a guild mate of yours.”<br><br>“Well met Maut.  What can I do for you?  Or do you just like to watch?” Salura said half jokingly and half sarcastically.<br><br>“I’m just here to see the newest member of the guild.  And to assign you a quest from the guild.  I need you to go to the Karanas and collect for me some pelts.  Do you accept?”<br><br>“Yes, m’lord.  I’ll do as you command.  I’ll be on my way immediately.” Salura saluted and began to leave on her task. “Crayne, I’ve got to head to the Karanas, I’ve a job to do for my guild.  When I’m free again, I’ll return here.”<br><br>“Take care Salura, good luck on your task.” Crayne said absentmindedly as he commanded his pet to slay a lion that just happened to have the misfortune to be walking by.<br><br>Salura made the long run through the East and West Commonlands and through the dangerous Kithicor forest eventually making it into Highpass.  The Highpass guards chased her out of their areas each time she got near them, but eventually Salura was able to get a passerby to cast an invisibility spell on her so she could slip past the guards and through the city. <br><br> Drow are not well liked, being that they are the mutated creations of Innoruuk.  Created through centuries of torturing elves underground, resulting in the almost blue skin color and incredible night-vision, as well as the proclivity towards evil, madness and pure hate.  Shadow Knights, being the evil servants of the dark Gods only added to Salura’s difficulties when traveling to unfamiliar cities.<br><br>As she reached the city, Maut’s voice spoke to her “Collect as many pelts as you can carry, from all the beasts in the area.  When you are ready, send me a tell, a telepathic message, and I’ll pick you up at the druid rings.”<br><br>Salura ran through the woodlands, killing all types of beast and collecting their pelts as she was instructed.  It took many hours to fill her packs and she’d completely used all her bandages binding her wounds from the battles.  Aching from her injuries and tired from battle Salura contacted Maut and rested just out of view of the druids at the druid ring.  Druids, being the servants of the Goddess Tunare, Innoruuk’s nemesis, wouldn’t waste a second in killing a Drow Shadow Knight.<br><br>A wood elf druid ported into the druid ring and as he stepped away from the ring turned into a Drow, it was Maut.  Salura began to wonder about this mysterious member of her guild.<br><br>“What class are you?  I’ve not seen a blade, but see that you teleport.  But you are no wizard and Tier’Dal cannot be Druids.” Salura quizzed Maut.<br><br>“Ah, but there you are wrong.  I am a Druid.  But unlike most druids, I wasn’t born into this life, not did I choose it.”  Maut said as he collected the pelts Salura handed him.  Salura gave Maut a skeptical look.<br><br>“You are wearing a guise.  You aren’t really a Tier’Dal.”  <br><br>“No, you have it backwards.  The wood elf is the guise I use to be able to travel safely.  Allow me to explain.  But first…” Maut began to cast a spell, healing Salura’s wounds.  Then Maut cast an array of spells on her improving her armor’s class, increasing her ability to take hits, and making her armor sprout thorns to injure her opponents.  “Hunt and I’ll heal you.  And I’ll tell you about myself.  Good job on the pelts by the way.  I’ll use them to fashion some nice items for you.  You passed my test and I’ll report your progress to Zanthor.”<br><br>Salura moved out around Maut in a circular pattern, killing all mobs she encountered as Maut provided healing support and welcome conversation.<br><br>“I was once a Shadow Knight like you.  I was sacrificed to Innoruuk as a tithe from the guild to him.  When I was resurrected, I was cast into being a druid by Tunare.  I don’t know what the gods have planned for me, but so it is.  I serve as the guild’s quest officer, testing new recruit’s loyalty and ability.”<br><br>Salura sent a quick tell to Cymbaline and Crista “I’m here in the Karanas with Maut.  Is this true he’s a Drow druid?”<br><br>“Crista was the first to reply “So Maut found you already.” Crista’s laughs filled Salura’s mind “Yes, it’s true.  I was there, at the ceremony.  Stay there, I’ll be right there.”<br><br>Cymbaline’s response was much like that of his wife’s.  A few kills later, the Drow pair came into view and Salura wiped the gore off her blade and armor and removed her helm to great her mentors.<br><br>“Good Gods Salura!  I had no idea how lovely you were.  You are as lovely as you are dangerous.” Maut said as he clasped Cymbaline’s arm in greeting.<br><br>Cymbaline growled something softly into Maut’s ear, and Maut laughed in reply.  Crista looked disapprovingly at Maut, then shrugged and smiled.<br><br>“Well, I had planned on introducing you two myself, but since you’ve already met.” Cymbaline held out his hands in a gesture of not knowing what to do next and looked to Crista.<br><br>“Sal, Cym and I need a quick word with you.” Crista said more to Maut that to Salura.  Maut nodded and selected a woodland lion a few yards off to kill and began after it.<br><br>“We know you are an orphan, and we’re sorry for your loss.  We’ll do all we can to help you find your siblings, or at least find out what happened to them and who is responsible.  These past few days we’ve been quite impressed, and your fast completion of Maut’s quests makes us very proud.” Crista said as she took Salura’s hands into her own, removing Salura’s gauntlets.<br><br>“We are so proud in fact, that if you will have it…” Cymbaline said as he looked from Salura’s hands to Crista then back into Salura’s eyes “Crista and I want you to do us an honor or two.”<br><br>“I’ll do anything you ask; you both have been so kind to me.  I owe you more than I can express.” Salura said, looking from one to the other.<br><br>“Cym has asked me to marry him, officially.  In a ceremony in front of the guild.  Will you stand as my maid of honor?” Crista said as a smile danced in her eyes and Salura saw a slight blush rise on Cymbaline’s cheeks.<br><br>“The honor is all mine.  That’s so cool!  I hadn’t realized you weren’t already married.” And Salura let out a shout of “Woot” that echoed off the hillside.<br><br>“Well, that’s not the end of it” Cymbaline said, as he took one of Salura’s hands in his own “I, err, we want to adopt you.  If you’ll have us as your parents.”<br><br>Salura stammered, lost for words and choked with emotions.  All she could do was nod and say thanks softly.<br><br>“Welcome to the family Ater’Mors!” Crista said as she deftly and with lightning speed drew her dagger and nicked Salura’s ring finger on her right hand.  Salura jumped, more out of surprise than pain, but Cymbaline and Crista had expected it and their grip on Salura’s hands, although gentle, it was firm.  Crista nicked her and Cymbaline’s finger in the same way and pressed all three of their fingers together.<br><br>“Bound by blood, we are a family.  Long live Clan Ater’Mors!” Cymbaline said as he withdrew his own hand.<br><br>“What does the surname Ater’Mors stand for?” Salura asked,<br><br>“It’s in the old earth language Latin and means “dark death”.  A fitting name for Tier’Dal Shadow Knights and Rogues.”<br><br>“A name to be feared, that’s to be certain.” Maut said.  The trio hadn’t noticed his approach.<br><br>“Maut, meet my daughter, Salura Ater’Mors.” Cymbaline jokingly formally presented his new adopted daughter to his longtime friend.<br><br>“An honor and a pleasure.  Congratulations Salura.” Maut said as he very dramatically took and kissed the back of Salura’s hand and made a deep bow.  Salura blushed and in a matching dramatic and uncharacteristic style curtsied, drawing loud laughs out of the group.<br>Chapter 3-Dream Voices<br><br>Salura was nervous, Crista was late.  Salura scanned the forest for her adopted mother anxiously.  It wasn’t like Crista to be late for anything.  And Salura couldn’t send a tell to here mother.  Salura feared the worst.<br><br>Members of the Band had already begun to consume copious amounts of every type of alcoholic beverage that was on hand.  Runners had even been sent to Neriak to get more.  The guild was getting boisterous and many members were randomly getting up and dancing with whomever was close.  Salura was getting exhausted from all the dancing, being one of the few ladies in the guild to all the many men.  Some members dueled each other for bragging rights, while others had drunken foot races.  A Guide appeared and started handing out cakes.<br><br>“I’m here.  Is Cymbaline furious?”  Crista’s soft voice touched Salura’s mind.<br><br>“He’s just standing here with Alma and Zanthor, as nervous as I’ve ever seen him look.” Salura replied mentally, adding a touch of laughter to her thoughts. “The guild is assembled and ready.  I was getting worried that something terrible happened.  Is everything alright?”<br><br>“I had the hardest time waking up.  Curse the gods; they’ve made me late for my own wedding.  Can you stall them for a few minutes more?  I’ll give Cym a tell now and ease his mind.”<br><br>“Crista, Cymbaline would wait till eternity for you. But I’m sure he’ll be glad you didn’t have a change of heart.”<br><br>Salura looked over and could see Cymbaline relax, apparently getting a tell from Crista.  Salura stood up and clanged her sword against her shield to get the attention of the wedding revelers.<br><br>“On behalf of my mother, Crista, welcome.  We are honored by your attendance.  You’ve been invited to witness the marriage of Crista to Cymbaline Ater’Mors.  And with out any further delay” Salura smiled as she saw her mother approach “Here comes the bride.”  Cheers erupted that could be heard throughout the zone.  Many adventurers shouted back their inquires as to the noise, jubilation and congratulations.<br><br>The ceremony was quick and simple.  Father Alma, the Band’s high priest officiated as Zanthor looked on along with his guild.  Salura couldn’t help stealing glances at the dashing Drow druid, and shyly blushed and looked away when his gaze caught hers.<br><br>Salura danced too much and drank even more.  She danced with trolls, ogres, humans, elves, and even a skeleton pet or two.  Salura couldn’t remember ever being happier.  But then, Salura still couldn’t remember further back than the day she woke in the Shadow Knight guild.  That seemed so many years ago, almost like it happened to another person.<br><br>Still feeling the hangover, Salura accompanied Scrillo, a fellow Drow SK and guild mate to the Karanas where they hunted Treants.  Scrillo although younger, was far more experienced and taught Salura many techniques she hadn’t picked up on her own.<br><br>While Salura slept, she had the strangest dreams.  She dreamt she was a cleric, learning the ways of magic in the halls of Neriak.  When she woke she could have sworn she had heard someone call her name and speak to her.  But after looking around she knew she was alone, curled up and hidden at the base of the tree near her hunting camp in the Karanas.<br><br>The dreams persisted, and were more real each time.  Salura mentioned her dreams to her family and guild and no one knew what to think of it.  After many days, Salura was convinced she was losing her mind.  Until one day when a bard messenger tracked her down and delivered a note.  The note read:<br><br>“Sister Salura, I hope this note finds you well.  I’ve been searching many months since my release from cleric training in Neriak.  Ulraz has told me what he knows about you, and from my inquires among the peasants of Norrath I’ve learned of your exploits.  Our parents would have been proud.<br><br>I’m still researching the events of that night when our parents were murdered, and I’ve not found anything new.  I have been able to locate our brother Noril but cannot meet with him as yet.  <br><br>I’m having the strangest dreams, and guess that you are as well.  I dream of the open plains of the Karanas, a place I’ve only just read about.  And in those dreams I wield a deadly blade, the blade of a Shadow Knight.  It was these dreams that led me to Ulraz, and he led me to you.<br><br>Come back to Neriak so we can meet. <br><br> Fondly, your twin brother, Salur.”<br><br>Salura rolled up the note and tucked it into her pack.  Immediately she broke camp and sent a message to her guild.  “I need to get to Neriak fast.  Any porters available?”<br><br>“I’ll port you, head to the druid ring for pick up, I can get you as close as West Commonlands, and I’ll cast Spirit of the Wolf on you to increase your running speed for the rest of your run.” Maut replied.  Within minutes Salura was whisked away and dropped into the West Commonlands.  Barely waiting long enough for Maut to Cast Spirit of the Wolf on her she was off and running.<br><br>Salura tried several times since receiving Salur’s note to contact him by tell, but each time there was no connection.  Salura inquired to the Neriak guards about her brother, but none had seen him recently.  Salura checked in to the forge house and sat by the fire.  Sensing the innkeeper’s disapproval, Salura ordered a light meal to make him happier.<br><br>Salura waited many hours, her barely touched meal had long ago grown cold.  Each time the inn door opened Salura looked expecting to see her brother, whom she didn’t know.  Salura wondered what he’d look like, would he be a priestly figure clad in robes, or a battle cleric with armor.<br><br>“I’m here sister, but cursed.  It seems only one of us may roam Norrath at a time, while the other sleeps.  I’ve made contact to Noril, Damdara, Hobbe, and Gospasha through their dreams, like I’m contacting you now.  Remember this when you wake up and know that I’m working to remedy this somehow.”  <br><br>Salura woke with a jump that sent the inn table flying and her meal scattering to the floor.  The inn patrons looked at her quizzically and the scowl from the innkeeper made Salura want to plant her boot between his eyes.  She hurled a couple platinum pieces to the innkeeper instead as she stomped out to her room to collect her gear.<br><br>“Cursed” she thought.  “More Erudite mayhem.  At least I know my siblings are alive. But now what to do?”  Salura headed out of Neriak on her way to the Temple of Cazic-Thule to join Scrillo in a hunting group.<br><br>After many grueling hours of killing lizard men known as the Tae Ew, Salura prepared to camp for the night, leaving instructions with the guild to look or Salur and make contact with him if he were to be seen.  As an afterthought, Salura added the names of her other siblings to the list of people to look for and settled into her hiding spot in a corner of a hallway in the Temple of Cazic-Thule and went to sleep.<br><br>“You there!  Stop!  I need to talk to you!” Maut said as the Tier’Dal almost ran past.  “I’ve been looking for you.  I’m a friend of your sister’s.” Maut explained as the Dark Elf turned to see who was calling after him.  “You’re Salur, right?  Salura’s twin…She told us all to be looking for you.”<br><br>Salur’s expression of annoyance was instantly replaced by one of hope.  “Sorry, thought you were going to ask for a heal, buff or rez.  This zone is making me crazy.” Salur said as he offered his hand for handshake.<br><br>“I’m Maut.  Salura had me port here near here to meet up with you.  She said that she couldn’t meet up with you and for the guild to make contact.  So here I am.  What do we do next?”<br><br>Salur pondered the question, his eyes downcast.  “I need to find a way to break this curse that keeps the family apart.  Until the time I find a counter to this curse, each of the siblings must train alone.”<br><br>Salur spent many months hunting and searching.  In dreams he and Salura became quite good of updating each other on their progress.  Salur eventually was offered membership into the Band.  For Salur, life was hard, but routine.  <br><br>Noril, Damdara, Hobbe and Gospasha began to also get in touch with the twins through dreams.  A note drop system and bard messages were used to augment the dream communication system.<br><br>From the collective memories of the six, and all their efforts to determine what happened that fateful night it was apparent that someone had intended to kill the whole family.  The assailants slipped into the home, and killed their parents first, then intended to kill the rest of the family.<br><br>Salura slept fitfully, and in her dream she recalled, finally, the events of that dreadful night she last saw any of her family.<br><br>Salura had heard a noise and called out telepathically to Salur “Wake up!  Intruders!” and sprang upon the nearest robed figure.  Within seconds Salur was in the room, having sprinted down the hall from his own into the room where his three sisters slept.  He began casting root spells and then damaging spells until it was apparent that Salura was in danger of dying.  Hobbe and Damdara, being younger and not yet trained in any class beat upon the intruders with their bare fists.<br><br>A loud bang and a blast of air knocked the children off their feet.  Salura looked to her twin as the leader of the robed figures chanted and all went black.<br><br>The spell should have killed them all.  But it had backfired, knocking them unconscious instead of killing them.<br><br>“Fool!” Hissed one assailant to an other “They live!  Now what?!”<br><br>“I don’t know why the spell failed.  Let’s just cut their throats and be done with it.” The second assailant said as he drew a dagger from his cloak and grabbed Salura by the hair and drew the dagger across her throat.  The dagger failed to even scratch the skin.<br><br>“They are protected somehow.  I can’t harm them.  We are in major trouble.”  A third assailant began to panic as he tried to stab each of the siblings but couldn’t harm a hair on any of their heads.<br><br>The leader began to chant a spell; a golden aura surrounded the Tier’Dal siblings.  “We may not be able to kill them now, so I’ll wipe their memories and then I’ll scatter them throughout Norrath so they may never band together against us.  I’ll change their forms so they will never be able to return to Neriak.  I’ll put a sleep curse on them so none can be conscious while another is awake.  We will be safe.”  <br><br>Damdara was morphed into a Wood elf and teleported to the tree city of Kelethin.  Gospasha was changed into an Erudite and sent to Erudin.  Hobbe assumed the form of a Barbarian and awoke later in Halas.<br><br>“Where’s Noril?” the leader asked his group.  Each member looked around them and shrugged their shoulders.<br><br>“He’s not here.” Answered one of the cloaked assailants.<br><br>“No bother.  This curse will strike him wherever he stands, no matter how far away.” The leader said as he turned his attention to Salur and began chanting the curses and spells again.  “I can’t change these two’s forms.  All other spells work but that one.  Somehow they are protected.”<br><br>“Guards!  Run!” an assailant lookout shouted to his group.  The leader quickly casted a teleport spell on Salur, sending him to Neriak, but the teleport spell on Salura fizzled, only sending her a few hundred yards away from her home.  <br><br>The Indigo Brotherhood patrol passed the home, noting the smell of burnt mama.  When they knocked on the door, no one answered.  Upon entering they discovered the murdered bodies of Salut and Rana.  There was no sign of the six children, except for the signs that they had put up a great battle with their parents murderers.  One guard found a torn piece of cloth, covered in blood.<br><br><br>Chapter 4-Love, Lies, and Betrayal<br><br>Salura continued her training as a Shadow Knight, but was far more interested in exploring Norrath than really setting her sights on becoming more experienced. The allure of discovering new zones was more exciting than training day in and day out fighting the same, never ending battles.  And Maut made it even harder for Salura to concentrate on her training.<br><br>Often Maut would whisk Salura away to some far flung corner of the continents of Norrath: Antonica, Odus, or Faydark.  There he would present gifts of foraged flowers to Salura and they would talk about their endeavors.  When the continent of Kunark was discovered, Maut took her to the Burning Woods and then to the Western slopes of the Dreadlands.<br><br>Salur continued his training, but the sleep curse prevented him from accomplishing much, since Salura was constantly awake, even if she was not training.  His armor was all handed down from Salura, along with a few gifts from Maut himself.<br><br>It was apparent to the Band that Salura had fallen for Maut, and that Maut was very fond of Salura.  Unknown to Salura, Maut was fond of lots of women.  Salura was no fool; she had guessed that Maut had many girlfriends.  Maut’s reputation for being a playboy Druid had gotten to Salura’s ears.  The cruelest cut was that it was a fellow guild mate, Vanannie that told inadvertently confirmed Salura’s suspicions.  No formal bond existed between Salura and Maut, so Salura wrestled with her feeling s of being used and what to do about her relationship with Maut.  Vanannie and Salura hatched a plan together to call Maut’s philandering out into the open once and for all. <br><br>The plan was to get Maut to propose to one of them, and then turn him down, citing his many other girlfriends as the reason, exposing Maut for the playboy he was.  During a guild meeting in the Arena, Vanannie and Salura hinted to Maut about formalizing their marriages.  But Salura had a change of heart and broke her pack to disavow Maut in front of the guild and instead of publicly humiliating Maut, Salura stood in front of her guild mates and proposed to Maut.  <br><br>Vanannie, knowing she had been betrayed by Salura and possibly preempted on her own scheme to trick Maut into marrying her, Vanannie told Maut about the pact.  Maut was furious and killed Salura on the spot.  The guild was stunned; no one had a clue about the plan to draw Maut out.<br><br>Maut fled the guild and headed for parts unknown.  Alma rezzed Salura and Salura explained the whole incident to the guild and took the wrath of the guild for attempting to trick Maut, although Maut wasn’t exonerated for his womanizing either.<br><br>Many days later, Salura was contacted by a Shaman who said he had a message from Maut.  Salura was reluctant to have anything to do with Maut, but the Shaman explained that Maut had gotten himself into a predicament and needed her help desperately.  Still fond of Maut, even though any chance of a relationship was out of the question, Salura agreed to meet Maut with the Shaman.<br><br>Salura waited in the Ferrott with the Shaman for Maut.  When Maut appeared, he was in wolf form.  The Shaman explained that Maut was cursed, having read a trapped spell scroll.  Maut was unable to change forms and unable to speak any language other than wolf.  Maut was able to communicate to the Shaman only after the shaman drank a potion that allowed him to converse in wolf.  The Shaman offered Salura a dose of the potion.<br><br>The potions tasted like lichen poured through a snake skin and it made her gag.  But after a few seconds from swallowing the horrid draught Salura could hear Maut’s voice in her mind again.<br><br>“Salura, I’m sorry.  I shouldn’t have been leading you on the way I did.  And although you were wrong to try to embarrass me, I shouldn’t have killed you.  I forgive you.  Can you forgive me?” Maut’s voice echoed in Salura’s mind.<br><br>“I’m sorry too.  I’m past being angry with you.  I have been thinking how I need to concentrate more on my training, not hopping around Norrath with a druid.  The Shaman said you needed my help.  What do you need? Salura replied to Maut.<br><br>“To break the spell, I need two souls captured in a bottle, and then we need to deliver it Nagafen’s lair, where we need to spend an evening fighting the monsters there.  Vincecross is collecting the souls as we speak.  Zanthor will accompany us to Naggy’s Laid and watch over your safety.  Will you go with me?”<br><br>Salura agreed to take the journey and Maut ported them to the Lavastorm Mountains.  From there they made an uneventful run to Naggy’s Lair, where Vincecross and Zanthor were already waiting.  The Band killed many kobolds that night, and as dawn broke outside the caverns of Naggy’s Lair, Maut’s curse broke.<br><br>Maut had a surprise for Salura.  Once again his old self, he asked Zanthor to bless his marriage to Salura.  Salura was taken by surprise, but agreed to marry Maut.  Zanthor announced the marriage to the guild, and there was much rejoicing.<br><br>Although married, Salura and Maut rarely saw each other after that night.  Salura was concentrating on her training and working on a counter curse to free her siblings.  Maut was busy discovering new and dangerous lands.  Lands so dangerous, Salura couldn’t join him.<br><br>Salura had taken to hunting again with Scrillo in the newly discovered lands of Velious.  Scrillo was advancing rapidly through his training as a Shadow Knight and showed Salura his favorite training grounds.  Often he had new armor and weapons from his conquest that he proudly showed off to Salura, and then would give Salura his unneeded items.<br><br>The Band of the Black Hand grew in numbers and strength.  The more experienced members were beginning to raid the planes.  Salura, still too inexperienced to accompany them, felt left behind by her friends and became more distant.<br><br>Salura's adopted parents divorced, and each remarried someone else.  Crista married Zanthor, completely taking Salura by surprise.  Cymbaline lost touch with his adopted daughter, married and later left for adventures in another dimension.  Occasionally sending Salura a tell just to let her know he still thinks of her.<br> <br>Crista and Zanthor added to their family by adopting an Iksar Necromancer named Kaloe and a Wood Elf Druid, Kynaen, adding to Salura’s list of family, although only by adoption and marriage.<br> <br>Salura was incredulous!  A Tier'Dal marrying an Ogre was one thing, but to adopt a child of Tunare was too much.  Salura much rather hunt with her other adopted sister, Kaloe, even if Kaloe was a scaly lizard.<br> <br>As time went on, Gospasha and Kynaen became friends as they tore up the Karanas and Blackburrow together.  And through Gospasha's friendship, Salura learned that not all children of Tunare are all that bad.<br> <br>So Salura befriended Kynaen and found that Kynaen was great company in hunting parties.  That's how Salura, and the Clan Ater'Mors, has been able to overcome their hate and racial prejudices and come to call a druid &quot;brother&quot;.<br> <br>Salura still is wary of the light lovers, and still owes a debt of vengeance to the Erudites that killed her parents and left her and her siblings orphaned.  But those enemies and their allies don't often venture out of their cities or their places of work, and can't be considered the same as their adventuring brethren.<br><br>The membership of the Band swelled, and many new recruits joined the Band.  Salura’s friend from long ago Crayne, was among the new additions to the guild.  Crayne and Salura terrorized the West Commonlands tollbooth guards for many weeks until Salura was near her 35th level of training.<br><br>One day, while Salura was camping in the Southern Dessert of Ro looking for the elusive Ancient Cyclops she heard a commotion among the guild.  From the sound of it, Maut had gone stark raving mad.  The guild asked Salura to try to calm her husband.  Maut was hurling insults at his guild mates and life long friends.  When Salura attempted to calm Maut he verbally attacked her honor.<br><br>Maut challenged anyone from the guild to a duel.  He claimed none could kill him.  Salura accepted the challenge, knowing there was no way that she could ever kill the far more experienced and powerful Maut.  Many others also accepted the challenge.  When Salura arrived in Lavastorm, the bodies of her fallen guild mates were scattered about Maut’s feet.<br><br>Maut was insane.  He claimed that he was the one true Maut, freed from his lifelong curse of being a Tier’Dal, he was now truly a Wood Elf and Maut Trueguide was dead, Maut Timbul killed him.  Maut denounced his friends, his wife, and his guild.  Maut killed all that dared to accept his challenge, including Salura.  Still aching from being resurrected, Salura limped back to Neriak where she nursed her wounds, collected supplies and left Antonica for Kunark, never to return.<br><br>Salura had finally entered her 40th level of training while in The Overthere hunting in pickup groups, doing whatever it took to forget about Maut.  Maut Timbul had been seen wearing the badge of the Brotherhood of the Spider, but the Maut Salura and the Band knew was gone forever.<br><br>Zanthor chose to retire and passed leadership of the guild to Vincecross.  Shortly after her adopted father’s retirement, Vincecross promoted Salura to an officer of the guild.  Salura spent a good amount of time badging new guild recruits and planning training sessions for the less experienced members.<br><br>Not too long after, Vincecross left the Band to join Noble Blade, passing leadership to the heir apparent, Salura.  Salura was too inexperienced to run a guild alone, the daily tasks of running the guild were overwhelming.  Salura was not enjoying being the guild leader.  The sudden loss of many members to either retirement of larger, more powerful guilds decimated the Band.<br><br>The Band took on many new recruits, straining Salura’s time and the guild resources.  Salura confided to Crayne many of the stressors of being a guild leader.  Crayne and Kaloe were the two people she turned to for encouragement.  Meanwhile Gospasha and Kynaen were exploring the western zones of Antonica.<br><br>Crayne was constantly by Salura’s side, so it came as no surprise when they announced they had run off to Kunark and eloped, with Crista as the only witness.  With the marriage, Crayne accepted the surname Ater’Mors and Salura shared leadership of the guild with her new husband.<br><br>Crayne didn’t get along with many of the members of the guild, often getting into quarrels with the membership. Crayne expected complete trust and obedience from his members, but the members refused to follow their new co-leader since he hadn’t yet proven himself as anything more than the husband of Salura.<br><br>The mood of the guild was mutinous.  Salura did her best to calm the arguing parties, but often found herself in a no win situation, having to choose between supporting her husband and co-leader or members of the guild.  Often, she privately reprimanded Crayne for being heavy handed and rude to the members.  She counseled him on how to lead with compassion and how to lead the guild through helping them achieve their goals, not only his thirst for power and prestige from other guilds.<br><br>Salura was awakened by Kaloe one night.  The guild was massing for a raid on South Ro to lure the Ancient Cyclops out for members to get his Ring of the Ancients.  Salura had left Crayne in charge of the raid and was taking the day off, feeling very ill.  Kaloe didn’t have any good news for Salura.  Crayne was disbanding members from the guild as they reported for the raid.  Crayne officially declared the guild disbanded, and had their charter removed from the Registry of Norrath.<br><br>Salura came to South Ro to put a halt to Crayne’s tyranny, but Crayne had eluded her.  He had joined up with Grave Wisdom.  Crayne’s action in destroying the Band was his initiation task to prove his allegiance to Grave Wisdom.  After several days, Salura was able to reach Zanthor and have the charter re-established.  Salura spent the next month locating and re0inviting members back into the Band.<br><br>But things were never the same.  Salura lost her enthusiasm for the guild and the weight of leadership wore her usually friendly and humorous demeanor down into depression.  Salura decided it was time for her to step down and let someone else lead the guild.  So Salura handed off her leadership and left the Band entirely, proclaiming self-exile.<br><br>Through this, Kaloe was her constant friend.  Kaloe kept Salura informed on the status of the Band even though Salura claimed to not want to know.  Things deteriorated rapidly after Salura’s departure and Zanthor returned from retirement to take care of the guild.<br><br>Salura was in Neriak when she heard about a huge battle that was ragging in East Commonlands involving her former guild.  It seems that Maut was again in battle against anyone wearing the badge of the Band.  Salura choose to not get involved and continued practicing her tailoring.  Salura was getting ready to free Salur.<br><br>Chapter 5-Freedom<br>The druid awoke slowly as the rising sun peaked over the mountains, casting a golden glow on the valley. Standing and stretching Dara scanned the area, taking in all the activities of the animals wandering nearby.  Somewhere, she knew, her family was out there, looking for her.  Dara quickly started a fire and began to cook the food she foraged.  Some rabbit and vegetables made a good stew.  Today would be a long journey.  <br><br>As Dara began to break camp and head on her way, a figure strode into view on the path.  A human female Dara could tell from far off.  Dara stood, a hand causally resting on her scimitar, ready for trouble should this stranger be a bandit or rogue.<br><br>“Hail, Damdara.  I’m a messenger of the Clan Ater’Mors.”  The stranger shouted out at the proper distance from the camp, which eased Dara’s nerves just a little.<br><br>“Well met, messenger. What news do you bring from my clan?  And call me Dara.  No one calls me by my given name.  Well, except for the twins.” Dara carefully regarded the messenger.  On the messengers back was a mandolin, the messenger was a bard, often used to pass messages along.  Bards, like druids, like to travel.<br><br>“Salur sends me to you.  He wishes you well and has good news.  Salura has made all the arrangements for you to see Salur soon.”  <br><br>“Wait, what arrangements?  Is there more?” Dara pleaded with the bard.<br><br>“That’s all he said, Dara.  I wish it more.  But if Salur’s right, then you may get to ask him yourself real soon.”<br><br>“True.  Thanks for carrying the message.”  Dara said as she reached into her coin pouch and produced twenty platinum coins for the Bard.<br><br>“Sorry M’lady.  I can’t accept payment.  You see” the bard said as she displayed a golden bracer “I’m bound to serve the Clan.”<br><br>“Bound to serve the clan?  Who are you? Who bound you?  I didn’t know the clan was more than the six of us.  Start from the beginning and tell me all of it.  Are you hungry?  I’ve some fresh rabbit vegetable stew.”  Dara said as she handed the bard a steaming bowl of stew and then sat beside the fire, ready for a long telling, if that was what was coming.<br><br>The bard accepted the bowl and likewise sat beside the fire, and collected her thoughts as she shoveled a few spoonfuls into her mouth.  It had been a long, tiring morning already. <br><br>“M’lady, I am Amord, messenger of your clan.  Recruited and bound by Salura to serve the clan.” The bard reported formally.<br><br>“Yes, yes. But tell me more.  And don’t be afraid.  I am completely unlike my sister, as my appearance proves.” Dara laughed at the look on the bard’s face at the last comment.  The apparent racial differences among siblings always confused many people.  Dara had grown tired of explaining it years ago.  She found it more fun to keep people guessing how her beloved twin elder siblings were Tier’Dal, yet she was Fier’Dal.  “I’m no Shadow Knight as you can see.  And despite my lineage, I serve Tunare, not Innoruuk, much to the torment of my elder siblings.<br><br>“Salura spoke of the curse.  That’s why Salur had the message sent.  That’s why I and the others were recruited.”  Amord noticed the druids ears perk up at the mention of other recruits and quickly added before Dara could open her mouth “yes, there are other recruits.  Ten of us I hear, all told.  Recruited by one of the twins.  To serve the siblings.  To add our talents to the family, so none is lacking.  As the Clan Bard, and human, I travel to pass messages among the Clan to all the world, except of course, the evil cities.  This is not a problem for the twins of course.” Amord stammered in a staccato voice, apparently hiding something.<br><br>“Out with it all bard, or face Tunare’s wrath!  What are you hiding? Dara began conjuring lightning, her fingers dancing with small sparks.  The bard could now see the family resemblance.<br><br>“The twins! One may die.  She won’t hear me out.  I tried to tell her.  I fear it too late already.  I told her the ritual was too dangerous.  She swore me to secrecy, and now I’ve broken that trust. Kill me, for that’s what Salura will do if she lives to hear of my broken oath.” Amord cried out and threw herself at Dara’s feet.<br><br>“Bard! Stop speaking in fragments or by Tunare I will put you out of your misery.  As for my sister’s wrath, she’s not here now, I am!  I can be just as deadly as she, or I can intervene for you between her.  But be out with it all, and quickly!”<br><br>“Salura has made a pact with Innoruuk to break the curse.  She’s to perform a ritual.  The recruiting of the mercenaries, like me, is part of the preparation.  Innoruuk wants her to build and lead a small force, one of every class.  She and Salur have been all over the world, even to the moon of Luclin, recruiting.  Then, once that was completed, they began training the recruits and equipping us.  We recruits have sworn an oath to the Clan Ater’Mors and in the process sold our souls to Innoruuk who the twins serve.  Salura was ready to complete the ritual when Salur sent me out to find the remaining four siblings.  I tracked you first; I’ve still to find Gos, Noril and Hobbe.”<br><br>“What does this ritual entail that it is so dangerous?” Dara asked softly, almost afraid of the answer.  Dara knew her twin’s god preferred very messy, bloody and deadly rituals and feared Salura had made a dear payment without consent of the rest.<br><br>“Salura is to be rededicated.” Amord said sadly.<br><br>Dara let the word bounce around inside her skull and felt it stab her heart.  Rededication to Innoruuk was not something Dara would ever want, even if she were a Drow.  Most that undergo rededication perish.  The ones who survive are never the same.<br><br>“Amord, in return for a rededication, Innoruuk will lift the curse?”  Dara asked the frightened bard, who after having let loose the worst of the news was looking a bit lightened of a burden, but worn from the telling.<br><br>“That’s my understanding.  And Salura was to get to it immediately.  She left for Third Gate this morning.”<br><br>“Lavastorm Mountains is the closest I can teleport to.  Let’s get going.” Dara stood and began to cast.  But Amord stepped out of the forming teleportation aura being cast by Dara and was left behind as Dara faded away.<br><br>Amord sat by the fire, and finished her stew.<br><br>The pain was excruciating.  She screamed until she could taste the blood from her lungs and throat.  She strained to control her thoughts, they were killing her.<br><br>She could hear the evil laughter.  He was enjoying this far too much she thought to herself.  She imagined her revenge, hatred swelled up in her, pushing aside the pain.<br><br>“Very good Salura, you’re starting to grasp it now.  Hatred, even for your god, will push away all other emotions, even pain.  But you will never truly kill me.  Sure, some may vanquish me in battle, if they bring enough trained forces.  But not before they taste my hate, like you are.”  Another bolt of hot pain filled Salura, throwing her to the ground.  Innoruuk laughed as the Shadow Knight contorted and writhed on the floor, cursing Innoruuk and hating him with all her being.<br><br>“That’s it Salura, hate me.  Your hate makes me strong.  The hate you will generate in my name makes me stronger.  Put all those silly thoughts of love aside.  Love is for the weak.  In this world there is only battle, death, deceit, and hate.”<br><br>Salura winced at the word “love” that was her downfall.  He love for her parents burned into hate for those who murdered them.  Her love for her siblings whom she cannot see brought her here for this torture ceremony.  Her love of Maut was the cruelest cut when Tunare reclaimed her servant and Maut spurned her.  Her need to be loved led her blindly into Crayne’s madness.  Yes, Innoruuk was right; there is no room for love in this world.   Salura reflected on her thoughts of love, and grew stronger as she turned them into hate.  Hate for being orphaned; hate for being alone; hate for being abandoned; hate for being deceived.  The pain subsided in waves as she gathered her hate.<br><br>Salura stood before her god, weakened from the ritual, but finally able to stand.  Glaring into her god’s face Salura exuded hate.  She had passed the ritual.<br><br>“Free me!” Salura shouted.<br><br>“Granted.” Innoruuk said as he faded away, back to the Plane of Hate.  The sound of the God’s mocking laughter filled the hall and the echoes bounced off the cavernous walls.  Salura wondered why she felt that somehow, she’d been tricked as she collapsed into unconsciousness.<br><br>Chapter 6-Reunions<br><br>Salur couldn’t see his hand in front of his face, the room was so dark.  How long he had been asleep was impossible to tell.  He strained to make out anything in the darkened room, but couldn’t.  He held his breath as he tried to hear anything that would clue him in about where he was.  All he could hear was the beating of his own heart.<br><br>Salur carefully stood, not wanting to crack his head on a low ceiling.  Salur fanned his arms out and above his head, feeling the thin air for a wall or ceiling.  Carefully he inched his way around the room, shuffling his feet to ensure he didn’t fall into a hole or trip over some unseen item.<br><br>Then he heard it, the sound was so very faint at first he thought he had imagined it.  It was a low rasp, the sound of something breathing.<br><br>“Hail!” Salur called out into the blackness, his words echoing back to him.  At least now he knew there were walls, and from the sound of the echoes, he was in a large room, maybe a cavern.  Salur strained to hear any reply, but there was none.  He couldn’t hear the breathing either.  Perhaps it was only his imagination, or maybe he scared of the creator of the noise.  Times like these, Salur wished he had learned an illumination spell or carried extra light stones in his pack, anything to help him see would have been a welcome relief.  Even with his innate ultra-vision, he still couldn’t make out any shapes, and his keen sense of hearing wasn’t much use either.<br><br>Groping his way along Salur walked forward, hoping to find a wall.  From there he could feel his way around for a door or way out.  He could teleport himself out, back to the cleric guild in Neriak’s third Gate, but that would leave this mystery unsolved.  Salur was too curious, and not in any apparent danger, so he saw no use in taking the coward’s way out.<br><br>“Salur?” said a weak, raspy voice from somewhere off to his right.  <br><br>“I am.” Salur replied to the darkness.<br><br>“Help.” was all the voice could summon, and that one word sounded like the last breath of the dying.<br><br>Salur dropped to his feet and crawled towards where the voiced came from as fast as he dared until he came across the foot of the person presumably calling to him.  Now that Salur had a target for his healing spell he stood and murmured the healing words.  The faint iridescent light cast by his spell enveloped the form on the floor for a fraction of a second.  The figure was curled into a fetal position, arms over its head, long white hair obscured a face, and the skin was unmistakably Tier’Dal.<br><br>Again Salur cast another healing spell, wondering how badly his target was hurt to require this much mana to heal.  The figure on the floor remained motionless.  Salur worried he was casting on a corpse.  Bending over, Salur touched the person on the floor, fearing he was too late to save them.<br><br>The body was still warm.  Salur traced his way up the form taking notice of broken bones that punctured the skin, large wounds bleeding profusely, and large welts across bare skin.  Salur closed his eyes, even though he couldn’t see, he didn’t want to see the damage on this poor person.  Tracing up from the foot Salur found his way to the victim’s head.  A tangled and matted ball of hair obscured the face, but he could feel the slight breeze of the victim’s irregular breathing.<br><br>Salur cast several more spells, some were healing spells, some spells to cure every type of malady he could thing of from poison, to disease, elemental damage from cold or heat, and spells to counteract magical attacks.<br><br>His magic casting mana temporarily depleted, Salur dropped down to the floor exhausted, hoping to meditate and regain his mana.  He placed one hand on his patient, afraid his touch may further hurt the unknown figure, but still wanting to be sure the figure was still alive.<br><br>“You’re pretty bad off my friend.  I hope my spells are easing your pain.  I hope you can hear me.  Know that I’m doing all I can to help you.  I can’t see a blasted thing in here.  I can tell you’re Tier’Dal, like me.  You’ve some vicious wounds, broken bones, and Innoruuk knows what else.” Salur trailed off, feeling like a fool talking to the darkness.  <br><br>Gently Salur ran his hands along his patient, trying to asses the condition of the wounds.  <br>“I’m just going to run my hands over your to see your wounds, I hope I’m not hurting you.  Don’t worry, I’m not trying to rob you or anything, not that you seem to be wearing much…”  Salur jerked away “I’m sorry! I had no idea you were female!”  Salur held his hands together, ashamed of having just inadvertently copped a feel of his patient’s breast.  Mentally Salur chastised himself for being such a clumsy ass.<br><br>“Don’t worry…”  The voice said weakly, but with forgiveness.<br><br>“I can’t express how sorry I am.  I’m a priest, sworn to celibacy.  I meant no offense.”  Salur stood and began casting a new round of spells to heal his patient.<br>“Don’t…worry…brother.”  The voice said, with a little more strength than the last time.<br><br>Salur stood staring into the darkness at his patient, his thoughts racing at being called brother.  Did the voice mean brother in the sense of fellow Tier’Dal, or was this indeed his sister, he wondered, speechlessly.<br><br>“Salura?”  Salur whispered into his patient’s ear.<br><br>“Ungh…yes.”  Was the strained reply.<br><br>Salur scooped his sister into his arms and cradled her, trying to will her to survive between his rounds of magic.<br><br>“Don’t you die on me now Salura.  After all this time, and all you’ve been through.  Don’t you die on me.” Salur wept bitterly, holding the lifeless body of his twin.  Hot tears streamed down his face, he struggled not to jostle her as he gasped for air between his sobs.  <br><br>“Who did this to you?!  I swear, I’ll kill them!  Then I’ll resurrect them so I can kill them again and again!  This will not go unpunished!”  Salur spat into the night.<br><br>Salur attended to his sister in the dark cavern for what seemed like an eternity.  With no way to measure the passage of time other than his hunger and the regeneration of his mana, Salur guessed it was several days before he felt Salura move on her own accord.<br><br>Salur had long ago used up his rations, and was now summoning food and drink magically, which didn’t taste as good.  He continued to cast healing spells on his sister whenever he had the mana to do so.  In between he divided his time between exploring the cavern, and sneaking a few moments of sleep as Salura drifted in and out of consciousness, but was still too weak to speak.<br><br>Salur continued to watch over his sister, mulling over the unanswered questions in his mind.  What happened to her?  What was keeping her so weak and wounded?  Would she ever get well, or would she die?  Where are they and how did he get here?  <br><br>He must have dozed off, because when he awoke, he could hear that Salura was sitting up, tentatively stretching and flexing her battered limbs.<br><br>“Good morning sleepyhead.”  Salura weakly teased.  “Got any of that summoned black bread and stale summoned water?”<br><br>Salur stood and summoned up a batch of each and handed his sister half of what he conjured.<br><br>“How are you feeling?  I’m so relieved to see you conscious.”  Salur said as he heard his sister scarf down mouthfuls of bread.<br>“Better.” Salura said between mouthfuls. “I’m starved, and I hurt like hell.  But nothing compared to before.  Now, where ARE we?”  Salura said as she started to stand.  “And where is my gear?”<br><br>“Best as I can figure, we’re in a cavern.  I couldn’t explore it very well, it pretty large and I can’t see a thing.  I haven’t come across any doors or opening, or any of your equipment.  I can gate out, but I’m afraid I won’t be able to get back to help you.”<br><br>“Gate out, and head to the Outpost in the Overthere.  I’ll find a way out and meet you there.  No arguing brother, get casting.  Don’t worry, I know what I’m doing.  Trust me.”  <br><br>Salur shrugged, knowing it was futile to argue with his twin, and began chanting the words to gate him out to Neriak.  From there, he had a long run to the teleportation book that would take him from Neklutos Forest to the Plane of Knowledge, where he then could teleport to the Overthere, just outside the outpost.<br><br>Salur disappeared in a soft aura as he gated out.  Salura sat and quickly rememorized her combat spells.  She cast a few spells to test what ones would give her some light to navigate by, and finding a spell that gave of a few seconds of illumination she recast it and worked her way forward until she reached a wall.<br><br>The stone was smooth, probably carved out of the rock by water eroding the softer stone from the harder stone over millions of years.  If that was the case, there will be a way out somewhere.  Continuing her hasty search of the area she found a couple bone chips, just enough to summon a skeletal pet.  <br><br>Luckily for her, the skeletal pet retained enough of its memories from his demise in this cavern to help Salura navigate a way out.  Salura never did find any of her equipment.  Which was fine, she thought.  She had sent the Ogre recruit Naram off with all the family possessions and money for safekeeping, along with the best pieces of her armor before the ceremony.<br><br>Salura emerged out of the tunnel into the dim caverns that she immediately recognized as Neriak’s Commons area.  Even if she hadn’t been able to tell from the familiar landmarks, the smell of Ogres and Trolls was unmistakable.  Salura reached out with her mind and sent Salur a message “I’m out.  I’m in the Neriak Commons.  I’m heading out to meet you.  I’m going to check my bank vault first to see if there is any gear still there.”<br><br>The vault was empty.  The banker was at a loss for an explanation, but Salura knew what had happened.  She was glad she had thought of sending Naram off with all she could carry before submitting to the ritual.  Hopefully, Naram still had all the items.<br><br>Salura navigated the passages of Neriak to the surface and Neklutos Forest.  Turning south she began running as fast as she could towards the Plane of Knowledge portal.  Waiting at the portal was a young Tier’Dal Magician.<br><br>“Hey Eari, nice of you to meet me. Did you run into Salur?”<br><br>“No M’lady.  I didn’t see him, but I just arrived a few minutes ago.  Was he to pass this way?”  The mage said as she kneeled in humility to the Shadow Knight, and her master<br><br>“No problem.  We are massing the clan for training.  Send word to the other recruits to meet in the Overthere.  Remind the light-loving races to beware the Dragoons that guard the outpost.  Salur is already on the way, and I’m heading there now.”<br><br>“As you wish.”  Eari complied.<br><br>“Tonight we train!  Tomorrow we conquer!” Salura said as she touched the magical pedestal with an opened book on it and disappeared. <br><br>The next few months, Salura and Salur were inseparable, training hard and gathering every copper piece and piece of salvageable junk that their vanquished foes died with at the hands of the evil twins.<br><br>When their travels took them past a town, the twins practiced their trade skills.  Salur was becoming quite good at blacksmithing. Salura was practicing all the other trade skills except for alchemy, poison making, and tinkering.  Those skills were already being taken care of by Hobbe and the new rogue recruit, Swiipe.<br><br>Damdara and the Iksar Monk Zatis had collected a lot of foraged items that were useful in practicing trade skills, mostly fresh vegetables, fruits and berries and such.  Also the hides of the various animals killed in training were laid into the family vaults and later Salura turned them into either wearable items of leather armor or armor padding for Salur to use in creating plate mail armor.  Every member of the clan, by blood or bond, was doing their best to collect whatever could be used to make battle equipment for the clan, or at least sold to buy more equipment.<br><br>Salura sent spies out to all the cities to create maps and scout for possible weaknesses.  Upon hearing the different reports Salura determined that she would need even more help than the clan of 16 she had.  Salura began to scour the taverns and other gathering places for news of guilds that may share similar goals as her clan.<br><br>Chapter 7-Friends and Allies<br><br>Salura had decided a good place for her to train would be the Dreadlands of Kunark.  She issued each member of the clan their training orders and set off for Kunark with Salur.  While the experience in the Dreadlands was good, the mobs were poor, usually only dropping the cheap gems, cheap armor and only a few platinum pieces, that after splitting among six group members, didn’t amount to much.  Occasionally a fine steel weapon would find its way out of a dead foes hand and into her magical packs, but it was hardly a way to maintain a small army.<br><br>Salura got to meet many adventurers from all races and classes of Norrath and its moon, Luclin.  Some were quite skilled and taught Salura tactics she had not learned on her own.  Some adventurers were friendly and generous.  Others were more annoying and conniving than Salura ever thought possible of an adventurer.<br><br>It was at a set of ruins outside Karnor’s Castle that Salura met the Paladin Horeb.  The dwarf was quite adept at sending mobs to meet their maker.  Salura allowed her hatred long enough to get to know the paladin for who he really was, not just as a light-loving dwarf paladin, but as a fine fighter and interesting group mate. <br><br>After many months of running into each other in the Dreadlands, a friendship formed between the two, despite the vast theological differences posed by their gods and their professions. It was Horeb who got Salura interested in a guild of capable adventurers called the Company of the Dragon. <br><br>Salura, with Horeb’s introduction, was accepted into the guild and met many fantastic professionals.  It was with these new found comrades that Salura first walked the Planes, specifically the Plane of Fear, home to Cazic-Thule, an ally of Innoruuk.  Salura, being the lowest level of experience of the raiding party had the dubious honor of introducing herself to Cazic in a ploy to lure him away from his post towards the raiding party who laid in wait.<br><br>When Salura awoke after feeling the Death Touch of Cazic-Thule, she knew why everyone was being so nice to her when she had been notified of her task to go meet Cazic.  She hoped the next time the raided the Plane of Fear that she would not be the newbie.<br><br> Shortly after Salura joined the guild, it merged forces with another guild and Salura was absorbed into Swords for Hire.  Swords for Hire were a great group of folks, very much like the members of the Company of the Dragon and Salura blended right in.  The guild was led by a lady bard named Emyric.  Emyric had lots of good officers assisting her and Salura was proud to be counted among the membership.<br><br>The ogre Shadow Knight and husband of Emyric, Bigting was very helpful in training Salura and was great conversation during long stakeouts of elusive foes that hoarded trinkets and treasures Salura sought after.<br><br>Over time, Salura grew restless.  The demands of her clan and the needs of the guild were in conflict.  One night Salura quietly slipped away from the Swords for Hire and out into the shadows alone.  Salura kept in touch with her friends and often Salura and members of the Swords for Hire would assist each other.<br><br>Salura bounced between restlessness and feeling confined; to being alone and longing for companionship.  Salura met many talented people as she explored.  Often the adventurers she bumped into often would eventually invite Salura to join the guild they belonged to.  Salura would join a guild and check out its leadership, goals, ability and discipline.  Most times Salura would leave just on the feeling that she did not belong, that somewhere there was a guild that she would truly feel at home with.  <br><br>The Ater’Mors banner flew with guilds such as the Legion of Ryu, One of the Chosen and Archons.  Salura met many talented professionals and fought valiantly to kill many foes with these guilds.  <br><br>But Salura grew restless and eventually resigned herself to keeping her clan unguilded.  Guild politics and drama as well as the needs and requirements of Salura or members of her clan made Salura think that she was unable to swear loyalty to any one guild for a long period of time.<br><br>Salura decided that a change of scenery and some adventure would lighten her spirits and headed off with Salur to investigate the newly discovered continent of Ykesha.  The continent was filled with pirates and their treasure.  There the twins perfected their skills in teaming up with each other. Salura would fight, and Salur would keep her healthy during battle.<br><br>Pirate treasure proved to be very profitable.  One day Salura arranged to have Salur meet her at the Gulf of Gunthak Lighthouse.  Salura had arranged for a surprise for her brother.<br><br>When Salur arrived, Salura was out by the drogmor pens.  These large lizards were the local equivalent of a horse.  They were big and smelly and came in all kinds of colors.<br><br>“Hey Salura.  Getting yourself a drogmor?  Salur asked as he watched Salura regard the different bests.<br><br>“Yeah.  But what color to choose?”  I checked with the merchant and I have enough platinum to buy a small drogmor summoning drum.  That means I only have enough to get a slow drogmor.  The faster the beast, the bigger the drum needs to be.”<br><br>“I’ve always been partial to black.” Salur wistfully replied, wishing he was the one buying the drogmor.  With a drog, Salur could sit up higher from the battle and cast his spells easier among the combatants.  Mounted on a drog, his foes would be less likely to attack him, favoring the unmounted opponents more.<br><br>“Here, go pay the merchant, get a black one.” Salura said as she tossed a bulging coin pouch to her twin.<br><br>Dejectedly, Salur went inside to pay the merchant for the magical drogmor summoning drum that would summon the beast.  Nine and a half-thousand platinum was all the Clan’s savings.  It had taken months of hard battle to accumulate the sum.  Salur wondered is he’d ever earn enough platinum to buy his own drog someday.<br><br>“One small black drum” Salur informed the merchant as he handed over the pouch of coins.  As the merchant handed Salur the drum, Salur felt and odd sensation as if he’d been spun around rapidly.<br><br>Outside, Salur met back up with his twin sister.  Salura has an odd smirk on her face, she was up to something.  Salur handed out the drum to his sister, but realized that no matter how hard he tried, he couldn’t let go of the drum.  Salura began to laugh at her twin.<br><br>“The drum is magically bound to you, only the purchaser can hold or sell the drum.  Consider it a gift in recognition of your new title of Vicar.”  Salura laughed as she strode off towards the path that would take them back to their hunting grounds.<br><br>Salur was shocked.  He had never thought Salura would purchase the drog for him.  But as he pondered it, it all made complete sense, especially the cold way Salura went about giving him his most wanted gift.  Ever since the rededication, Salura avoided anything that seemed like she was showing fondness to anyone, even her family.<br><br><br>Chapter 8-Reforging Old Bonds<br>Salur toils away over the red hot coals as Salura watches with great interest. “When can you make it, brother?  It would greatly help protect me in battle.”<br><br>“Patience sister, I’m not quite skilled enough to try to make that Dark Prince Regent Breastplate yet.  And you wouldn’t want me to botch the attempt and ruin the components, especially since some of those items were rather costly and hard to find.”<br><br>Salura sighs and unconsciously shifts her weight and fidgets with her battle worn gear. “How much more practice will you need?”<br><br>“Quite a bit, I’m afraid.  Keep gathering Acrylia, windstones, and essences of wind.  I’ll practice making the Acrylia armors until I’m confidant I can make your items.  We can sell the Acrylia and make some money back.  And tell Gospasha to get cranking on those vials of clear mana”<br><br>“She knows, she hasn’t yet attained that level of magic.  She and Kynaen from the “Holy Warriors of Faith” will be training these next few days.  When Gos attains here 29th level of proficiency, you’ll have a constant flow of mana for your smithing tempers.”<br><br>“Ok Salura.  Oh, I’ll also need some money, armor molds aren’t cheap.  And until the family store sells some of your equipment, we’re pretty much broke.”<br><br>“Well, we could sell your drogmor…Ugly, smelly beast.  Then again, I’m sure we won’t get much back for him.  Maybe we could sell him to a glue maker.”<br><br>“Oh, no you don’t!  I love that beast!  He may not be the fastest animal, but I’ve grown to count on him.  He intimidates our foes just enough to make them think twice about hitting me while I meditate in battle.  And it gives me a good view of the battle.”<br><br>“I was only kidding brother.  The Drog stays.  It’s just that your smithing components are very expensive.  Have you seen the prices in the Bazaar lately?”<br><br>“Yes, but once I make some Acrylia armor, we will make some money back.  Our merchant reports that we sold over 3k plat today.  I told her to use that money and buy the reasonably priced items I need.”<br><br>“Ok, when you run out of smithing components, join me and we’ll hunt the beasts for more.  To change the subject, I received a message from Kenronous from “One of the Chosen.  We are both negotiating on our clan rejoining with the OotC.  It seems the reasons for our departure have been dealt with.”<br><br>“Then I say we rejoin.  Or is it not as simple as that?”<br><br>“Well, Salur, we did leave quietly, with no word.  Although I burnt no bridges, I’m sure they are just as hesitant to offer a position as we are to accept.”<br><br>“It would be nice to be guilded again.  I could use some help in completing my quests. No offense sister, but we need more than just your blade to succeed. And I know you miss your friends Merk, Audry, Hurb and Nul.  And I know I miss hitting the dungeons with them.”<br><br>“Well, then it’s settled.  If an offer is tendered, then we will accept.  In fact, we may know as soon as this weekend.  I know our names are being discussed by the officers.”<br><br>“Oh, that’s why my ears are ringing.  I thought it was from the hammer hitting the anvil for too long.  I fear I’m losing my hearing from all this smithing.”<br><br>Many months later, Salura sat alone beside the campfire of her camp, absent-mindedly poking at the fire with a stick, deep in her own thoughts.  Since returning to the Guild of One of the Chosen, much had happened.  She and Salur had improved on their levels of combat experience.  Salur had completed the large epic quest to earn his coveted and much sought after Water Sprinkler on Nem’Ankh-a mana free resurrection tool, which makes clerics like Salur very popular with adventurers.<br><br>Gos had reached her 30th level of training as an Enchanter, and was now able to cast spells on adventurers to increase the rate of mana regeneration.  Adventurers donated well for Gos to cast this addictive spell on them, often 10 or more platinum pieces, for once the duration of the spell faded, the adventurer felt they couldn’t hunt without it.  <br><br>Dara, having also reached her 30th level of her training as a Druid was now able to teleport adventurers to some of the far-flung corners of Norrath and its moon, Luclin.  Most adventurers would gladly donate 20 to 50 platinum pieces for Dara’s services.<br><br>Hobbe was progressing in her studies in Alchemy, but was only proficient enough to make the less popular selling potions.  The more popular potions sell for up to a hundred platinum for a stack of 10 potions.<br><br>Salur’s smithing skills were progressing nicely, but he still wasn’t skilled enough to attempt making the Blood Lord Regent armors yet.  The clan’s funds were continuously low, for as the members of the clan progressed in their training, they required new equipment, trade skill components, and spell scrolls, none of which came cheaply.   <br><br>Naram was often busy in the Bazaar selling the acquired loot from the slain enemies of the Clan.  Naram was so busy selling that she rarely had time to hunt and train for herself.  The few hundred platinum a week that Naram was able to turn in trade was greatly needed, but wasn’t enough.<br><br>Salura considered Noril, who would need his 29th level of spells soon.  That would easily cost several hundred platinum.  And then there were rest of the Clan, the remaining mercenaries, whom so far, hadn’t been called upon to perform, but were hard at work training to be ready to serve when the time arises.<br><br>With a total of 16 Clan members to provide for, Salura never had to wonder why she couldn’t afford to upgrade her own armor and weapons.  Salura wondered why she continued to abide by the task Innoruuk had ordered so long ago.  At every turn it seemed that this was a fool’s errand.<br><br>“Recruit, equip, and train an army, one of every career class of Norrath; as many races as you can accommodate” had been Innoruuk’s instructions.  Since then, there had been no further guidance, or any help.<br><br>Salura had hoped that the Clan would be able to recoup some funds from the sale of their wares, but the return was disappointing.  Salura seriously had to consider finding more profitable ventures to finance the Clan.<br><br>Perhaps if Salura completed some quests, she would be able to collect some rewards, or armor upgrades as payment.  Amord had brought word that Garadin, a Coldain dwarf in the Eastern Wastes of the Continent of Velious was seeking someone to perform a series of favors for him.<br><br>Then there was the prospect of participating in the Grimling Forest Wars.  The Shar Val were rewarding people for assisting them in their fight against their foes, the Grimlings.  And on the Continent of Ykesha, there was a quest or two that seemed to have good promises of rewards.  And mining Acrylia for Salur’s smithing or just to sell in the bazaar was also another option.<br><br>Perhaps it was time to recall Salur from his duties as teacher of the Clan.  Together, she and her twin could easily accomplish some tasks for payment, and then return to training the Clan.  Without funds, there wasn’t much more that the small army would be able to do.<br><br>Where to go first, Salura pondered.  There was always the prospect of returning to Highhold Keep, and slaughtering the guards there for their salaries and fine steel weapons.  Then there was hunting the Hill Giants in the Rathe Mountains.  The giants often carried a score of platinum, but this was a well know fact and the zone was usually crowded with adventurers seeking to empty their pockets of the Hill Giants into their own.<br><br>Salura slept fitfully by the fire that night, her unconscious still churning over her conscious thoughts.  By morning, Salura had made her decision and informed the Clan of the next course of action.<br><br>“I can’t feel my toes” Salur whined to his sister, not sure if she heard him and was ignoring him, or if his words were carried off in the seemingly never ending bitterly cold wind that seemed to suck the life right out of him, no matter how many resist cold spells he cast.  Salur even considered casting a fire based spell on himself, just to get warm, but decided against it.<br><br>Elenara approached and Salur wondered what magic she was using to protect her scantily clad body from the biting cold.<br><br>“Here Salur, the pelts I told Salura I had stored up in the vault.  Happy hunting.” Elenara said as she passed over several high quality walrus, tundra Kodiak and cougar skin pelts to her guild mate.”<br><br>“Thanks a ton!  This will make a couple Coldain Hunter Blankets.  Is there anything we can collect for you while we hunt this area?” Salur telepathically talked with Elenara.<br><br>“No, I’m done here.  I have finally collected all the snow griffin eggs I need to make the shawl.  You should start yours soon.”  Elenara’s voice filled Salur’s mind like warm sunshine.<br><br>“I should.  I will.  Since were hunting here helping Garadain anyways, I’m sure we can pick up the components I need.  That’s a great idea.  Thanks again Elenara.” Salur liked his guild mates and was happy that Salura was no longer being a hermit and was allowing the Clan more interactions with the guild.<br><br>“I’m off to sleep.  I’ve got this nasty cold.  Maybe after some rest I’ll feel better. Maybe we can hunt Wurms in the Great Divide for their glowing biles that I need to make the next shawl. Happy hunting to you both!”  Elenara said as she began making for her camp.  Salur tucked the hides into his packs and huddles closer to his drog, happy that the beast gave off heat, although it also gave off an equal amount of stink.<br><br>Salura continued to trudge on ahead, looking for the camp of the dwarves she had decided to aid in their quest, quickly slaying any creatures that she saw.  Salur was grateful he was mounted on his drogmor; at least he didn’t have to walk in the snow.  “Yep, good old Thunderhooves” Salur thought as he patted the thick scaly hide of his drogmor.  The beast was one of the slowest, but he was sturdy and intimidating.  Salur commanded his mount to follow Salura and Salur snuggled into his cloak and closed his eyes, partly to keep the ice crystals from digging into them, partly to meditate, and partly to get some sleep.  Salur knew his drogmor would follow Salura unless she ran off to fast or far ahead, which Salur also knew that Salura was being careful to not outpace Thunderhooves.<br><br>Upon reaching the dwarf camp, Salur pulled his drog up alongside the fire while Salura went into one of the huts to discuss the terms of the quest.  Several dwarves looked upon the twins and Salur could feel their admiration thought the exchanged glances and nods, even though no one spoke.  Conversation in the open in the Eastern Wastes was pointless; no one could hear you through the howling of the wind as it blasted the area.<br><br>“Hail Garadain” Salura said as she ducked through the low opening, even for a Drow, that was the dwarf’s entrance into his command post.  The stocky, battle hardened dwarf smiled when he recognized his visitor.  Having only known the twin Drow from their reputation among the Coldain, Garadain was excited to finally meet the Drow who had so gallantly fought giants in support of many Coldain causes.  Garadain, when he first had heard the stories of the deadly female Drow SK could hardly believe the stories of her assisting the Coldain.  After all, Drows, especially Shadow Knights, are known for their brutality and pure evilness.  In the dwarf city of Kaladim she would probably be chased out.  But the Coldain of Velious were a lot more forgiving, perhaps because of their long time separation from contact with the other continents of Norrath, mostly perhaps of their desperation for help, from any source, outlaw or not.<br><br>But Salura was no outlaw.  Not at least to the Coldains.  The Coldains regarded Salura as an ally, and were even more thrilled to learn she had a twin, who was also supportive of the Coldain.  Garadain saw the approach of the formidable duo even through the unrelenting ground blizzard.  It was hard to miss the huge lumbering, dark shape of Salur’s drog as they approached, but more specifically, they could feel them approach, the drog’s hooves pounding the tundra pre-announced their arrival.  As the twins got closer, Garadain saw Salura in the lead, leading her way for her brother the battle cleric.  <br><br>The twin’s armor, now painted in the chosen family colors of red and black, with signature golden bracers, was unmistakable.  Garadain had heard of the Clan’s reconstitution, the finding of the lost siblings, and the recruitment of mercenaries to complete their small army.  Now, as the lethal ally stood in front of him, fiercer than he’d even imagined from the tales he’d heard around the campfires, Garadain knew the stories were true, even if they were incomplete.<br><br>“Garadain, I heard that you lost your hunting blanket to the wild winds.  I’ve taken the liberty to fashion you another one.  And should you manage to lose this one, never fear, Salur is practicing to make you a spare one.” Salura said as she wrapped the dwarf warrior in a thick, warm blanket, made from two hides of snow cougars and two hides of tundra Kodiaks.  The quality of the work was exquisite, and the dwarf sank into the blanket as if in a dream.<br><br>“Thank you Salura.  As a token of your service to me, appreciation of this fine gift, and of our friendship, please take this Copper Coldain Insignia ring.  Show it whenever you need to prove yourself to a Coldain.  Those that know me will know its significance.”  Salura took the ring, too small for even her slender fingers and tucked it safely away into one of her magical pouches.<br><br>“Now, there is the matter of my nephew.  He’s out after that rabid tundra Kodiak again.  The shrilling of my sister is about to drive me insane, it’s even worse than the shrieking of this infernal wind.  She’s convinced he’s going to get himself killed, and truthfully, I can’t say I blame her for worrying.  He fancies himself a great Coldain Hunter, but he’s more of a momma’s boy.  Would you go after him and see to it that he doesn’t get himself into trouble?  I’ve got enough problems without having to worry about Boridain.  Here, give him this axe, it looks just like mine, but I’ve dulled the edges for his safety.  It can’t cut warm butter, but it’ll make him feel deadly.  Of course, you’ll have to kill the beast for him, but make it look like he did it, for his pride’s sake.  A little secret between us, eh?  Come back with word that the task is done and we can talk about your future endeavors with the Coldain.<br><br>“Sure, Garadain, I’ll look after your nephew.  I know how important family can be, and how difficult.” Salura chuckled as she examined the dull bladed axe before storing it in one of her packs.  “I’ll be back before you know it, keep warm.”<br><br>Garadain watched as Salura leaned close to shout into Salur’s ears.  Garadain had heard about Salur’s smithing prowess, although no one that wasn’t a dwarf could ever really be that good, but it was apparent that Salur had smither’s ears, dulled from the clanging of iron on the anvil for too long.  Predictably, Salur shrugged his shoulders, and cupped a hand to his ear, trying to hear and understand his sister.  Impatiently, Salura gave the “follow me” wave and pointed out to the tundra, in the direction of Boradain’s hunting camp.  The twins started off as they had come in, Salura in the lead, with the black drog following, bearing its magical master, disappearing out into the ground blizzard.<br><br>“Seriously Salura, why even try to talk, just send me tells?  This blasted wind makes any form of conversation impossible.” Salur sent the telepathic message to his sister’s mind.<br><br>“Because I long for the sound of a true voice.  The voices in my head, they had no form, no face.  At time I feel I’m going mad with all the snatches of conversations flying about among the guild in my head.” Salura shot back telepathically to her brother.<br><br>“Perhaps you long for companionship, other than just myself?” Salur chided.<br><br>“What do you mean by that brother?” Salura playfully replied.<br><br>“I’m the Vicar, the priest, not you.  We twins share a lot of traits, but the traits that are absent in one, are doubled in the other is all I’m saying.”  Salur grinned evilly as he looked to meet his sister’s eyes.<br><br>“Are you inferring that I long to share my bed again?”  Salura joked back.<br><br>“I long for that, but not for your reasons.  I’ve considered sharing my bed with the drog, just to keep warm.” Salur’s laughter echoed in Salura’s mind.  Salura gave Salur a mischievous look, raised an eyebrow and then regarded Salur and the drog and gave a dramatic shudder.<br><br>“Pretty desperate to sleep with a drog, brother.  You’d shame us all.” Salura teased.<br><br>“No worse than sharing a bed with an Ogre, Barbarian or Wood Elf sister.” Salur half-jokingly replied, scoring a shot on Salura’s ego.<br><br>“How would you know?  There’s something to be said for each of those men I had in my life, regardless of their race.  But put it from you mind Salur, I’m not longing for that kind of companionship.  Although…”   Salura’s thoughts trailed off from her conversation with her twin to distant memories.  Memories that provided an inner warmth to the otherwise frigid Drow.<br><br>Salur wondered what, or more correctly who, Salura was thinking of and could have sworn he actually saw a thin smile cross his sisters face, a small sparkle in her usually dull, blood red eyes.  <br><br>Chapter 9 Hot and Cold<br><br>Salur closed his eyes as he meditated, taking in the smells and sounds of the wharf.  Luckily, he was far enough from the docks and fish market and the accompanying odor of decaying fish.  Here he could hear the soft ding of the buoys and the crashing of the surf.  The breeze that came in from the ocean was clean but salty, a much welcome respite from his previous assignments in the frigid Eastern Wastes.  The sun beat down on his face and neck, warming the Drow cleric.  It was warm, but still not too hot to make his armor uncomfortable to wear.  To Salur, this was as close to a vacation as he’d had in years.<br><br>His reverie was broken by the smell of spent mana and the sounds of lightning arcing on skin, followed by the pungent aroma of charred flesh, most likely Ogre from the smell of it.  Salur was getting quite good at guessing what foe Dara was in battle with and what spells the young Druid was testing on her opponents.<br><br>Opening his eyes he saw the Ogre, struggling with the magical roots that ensnared his feet and legs and hindered his escape from the Wood Elf Druid.  Dara cast another spell and sat to meditate while the Ogre slowly succumbed and fell over dead on the boardwalk.<br><br>Nonchalantly Dara walked over to the corpse and kicked it over onto its back and began going through its pockets to see what gems and coins she could find.  It was hard to believe this Druid was a worshiper of Tunare, the Mother of all.  Tunare’s followers, or children as they liked to refer to themselves, were a free-spirited bunch.  They talked of love and following the light, completely opposite of what a follower of Innoruuk, the Prince of Hate is used to.  <br><br>Harder to believe is that Dara was born a Drow, destined to follow Innoruuk.  The transformation by the Erudite marauders was perfect, except for the battle lust that Dara exhibited-that was pure Drow, and if Salur closed his eyes, he could almost imagine Dara as the Drow she was before the spell that permanently transformed her into the form of a Wood Elf.  The family features were there, the high cheek bones and the slight frame.  A few thousand years living underground and she could pass for a Drow someday Salur joked to himself.<br><br>Dara lightly jogged over and sat on the boardwalk near Salur but out of stepping range, and upwind, of the Salur’s drog. “I need to meditate, I’m out of mana.  I’ve managed to collect several nice gems that should fetch a nice price.  Question is, should we sell them to the merchants in the Gulf of Gunthak, or forward them to Naram for sale in the bazaar?  What would fetch us the better price?” Dara said as she wiped the gore from her weapon and armor.<br><br>“Well, selling them to the merchant is fastest, but you can get a better price in the bazaar if you’re patient.  Another option is to see if Gos wants to use them for her jewelry making, then we could sell whatever she made.” Salur considered out loud.<br><br>“How long does Salura want us out here training?  I’m just curious.  Nothing wrong with thinning out the population of pirates on this continent, although it seems we’re hardly making a dent.  There’s just as many in that warehouse each time I go back.”<br>“Salura didn’t say how long.  The purpose of this camp is two-fold; training and financial.  I hunted here until I was level 57, so no worry about you getting bored too soon.  As for the financial part of it, I don’t know how full the family vault needs to be before she recalls us.  More than likely, she’ll interrupt us for small tasks, and have us return here for a long time to come.  Once you’re ready, you’ll be sent out to train the mercenaries again.  And I suppose Salura will then send Hobbe to train with me here.  And that’s fine with me.” Salur said as he stretched his arms wide as if hugging the warm sun. “Ahh, anything as long as it’s warm.  Let me see, thirteen members of the clan need mounts, at 9.5k or more each that’s 133 k platinum, not considering the costs of spell and armor upgrades.  We make about 500 platinum a day…so…”   Salur beamed a great smile and grinned evilly at Dara “I’d expect to be here quite some time, excepting raids and specific short assignments.”<br><br>Dara laughed at her brother’s apparent lightheartedness and joy for his new assignment.  There were worse places to be assigned to hunt, Dara agreed.  The stories Salur told of the Eastern Wastes were enough to make her shiver, even in the noonday sun in the Gulf of Gunthak.  But Dara yearned to explore, and being a Druid, the portals available to take her wherever she wanted to be were calling to her.  Being the Clans transporter was not a bad job.  She got to take members of the mercenary force all over the world and moon.  The promise of training the mercenaries was a task Dara couldn’t wait to be ready for.  She had trained many of the mercenaries up to the 15th level already, and left them camped in the Overthere until she completed her required rounds of training with Salur.  Noril, Hobbe, and Gos were already making their way to the lands of Ykesha, as ordered by Salura.  The mercenaries waited for Dara’s return to the Overthere.  The army was becoming stronger each week.<br><br>“Do you think she’s alright?” Dara asked, breaking the silence.<br><br>In Everfrost? I’m sure she can handle herself fine, don’t be silly.” Salur chuckled.<br><br>“I know she can handle the monsters and enemies that lurk there.  I meant…..never mind.” Dara shook her head, dismissing a thought.  “Why did Salura send you away?”<br><br>“Probably because she needs me to train you and to raise funds here.”<br><br>“But why didn’t she come too?  I thought you two were inseparable since the rededication.”<br><br>“Perhaps because she still has things to take care of, and had no need for my help.  Besides, I was freezing to death and she knew it.  This could be my reward for my part in the whole Garadain’s Quests.”<br><br>“Yeah, or maybe she just needed some privacy from you for a while.”  Dara teased.<br><br>Salur pondered the irony of that innocent comment.  Salur had unintentionally awakened part of Salura that had been long dormant through his last teasing conversations.  Did she get rid of him as a reward?  Or did Salura have other reason to want to be free of her twin for a time.  Had he hurt Salura with his joking over her past failed love-life, and the lack of one now?  Or is Salura yet again, keeping a secret lover?<br><br>Salura stared into the Coldain’s campfire, mesmerized the flicker and dancing of the flames.  As if hypnotized, Salura stared into the flames and tried to concentrate on the matters at hand, the continued upgrading of equipment for the Clan and their training.  Truly, she and Salur needed to complete their remaining levels of training, but founds we critically low.<br><br>After helping the Coldain as much as I can, what next?  Salur and Dara are raising funds.  I can send someone to farm pelts and silks in the Karanas.  But what of Salur and my training?<br><br>Looking at the moon Luclin high over head Salura counted the years and months it had been since the rededication.  Almost exactly 2 years.  She was in her49th level of training, Salur was in his 25th.  The other siblings had barely made their 20th levels.  Now Salura was in her 58th level, Salur closer to starting his 57th level, and all the other siblings were into their 30th levels.  The mercenaries, all recruited fresh from their guild halls, had been raised up from the first level and were now in their mid teen levels of training; some had even surpassed the others and earned the rights to their surnames after their 20th level of training.<br><br>Was this progress adequate?  Would Innoruuk be pleased?  Salura decided for now, helping the Coldains while Salur trains Dara and they collect funds is the best course.  Soon though, the twins would have to resume their own training.  Innoruuk had promised Salura an Unholy Steed, one of the fastest horses breed, when she completed her normal training.  Then there was the prospect of the advance training, specific skill developed solely for her class.  It seemed the demands on her and the Clan would be never ending. <br><br>Tonight, she accompanies Boridain on his quest to slay the rabid tundra Kodiak.  Funny thing about Boridain and this beast, Salura could recall tales of other adventurers helping Boridain kill a rabid beast also.  Boridain must be the Coldain equivalent of the incompetent dog-catcher, Salura mused to herself.  No matter, Garadain was still testing Salura’s skills and loyalty, a test Salura would pass with flying colors.  Salura sent a messenger to find Salur and to ask him to return for the night’s hunt.<br><br>Tonight we hunt rabid Kodiaks, tomorrow we pillage Dulak in the morning, and in the afternoon we twins walk the Plane of Sky.  Then Salur and I train.  Salura said as she unfurled her maps of Norrath, gazing over the names of the different cities and hunting zones, trying to decide where to take her brother to train.  The Plane of Nightmare had been a good hunting ground.  Wit the right addition of a few hunting party members, a lot of experience could be had in one evening.<br><br>Her decision made, Salura rolled up her maps and once again settled down to stare into the fire.  Having reviewed her plans and finding no flaws, Salura pushed thoughts of Clan management from her mind.  She needed to relax.  Her mind wandered from memory to memory, lingering on the fond ones, rushing past the painful ones.  Salura missed her adopted brother Kynaen.  It had been weeks since they briefly got together in Skyshrine to claim Salura’s reward for a quest there.  Salura rubbed the bracer and thought of Kynaen, more than an adopted step-brother, Kynaen was Salura’s best friend. “Perhaps he will show up tonight and help out.  Druids are so unpredictable.”  Thought the Drow.<br><br>The twins headed out from Garadain’s camp in the early morning, hoping to meet up with Boridain at his camp just to the North West.  In typical Eastern Wastes fashion, the wind was howling and a ground blizzard was raging.<br><br>It didn’t take long for the twins to Locate Boridain, and he was happy to receive the axe his Uncle sent.  Salura chuckled to herself at Boradain’s show of examining the weapon, testing its balance, grip and swing, but never noticing the dullness of the blade.  Boridain was no hunter.  Salura wondered if he could track the Rabid Tundra Kodiak, or if this was going to we an aimless sojourn though the Eastern Wastes.<br><br>Without much announcement, Boridain headed off to the North West, the twins silently following.  Salura scanned the area for any approaching foes and silently took care of them before Boridain ever noticed their presence or Salura’s absence.<br><br>Boridain walked right up to the front gate of the Frost Giant Fort and was about to challenge them to a fight, but Salur rooted Boridain to the spot, which really irked the small dwarf, while Salura dispatched the giant guards to meet their maker.  To sooth Boradain’s hurt ego, Salur cast atone on him, and wiped the event from his mind.<br><br>Boridain, convinced he had vanquished the fort guards, proudly stomped off to the north, hoping to find tracks of the rabid tundra Kodiak that was terrorizing his village.  Salur shook his head, a signal Salura knew all too well, even Salur wasn’t impressed with the young dwarf, and was dismayed at Boradain’s delusions of grandeur.<br><br>Boradain’s next stop would have been the Orc Prison camp, if Salura hadn’t anticipated the dwarf’s intentions once the group climbed the rise of hills overlooking the prison.  Quickly Salura slipped away from the party and killed the giant and Orc guarding the camp.  Boridain, upon seeing the camp was “deserted” headed south, back to his camp.<br><br>Dejectedly, Boridain mused aloud that he was no great hunter, having not been able to track the Rabid Kodiak.  Before Salura could suggest another venture out to search, a huge beast lunged at Salur.  The Rabid Tundra Kodiak had found them instead.<br><br>Salura and Boridain fought side by side and in a few short minutes, the Rabid Tundra Kodiak was dead.  Salura cut off the hide and gave it to Boridain so he could show his village proof of his deed.  The little dwarf was so happy, but realized in the excitement, he’d broken his uncle’s axe.  Boridain gave it to Salura to return to Garadain, with Boradain’s apologies for breaking it.<br><br>Back at Garadain’s camp, Garadain was happy his nephew survived the fray, and rewarded Salura with a silver Coldain Insignia ring, and asked her to do another favor for him.  This favor was to fashion a Coldain hunting knife, which Salura did after a quick trip into Thurgadin to use a forge.<br><br>Garadain was so impressed with the knife he once again rewarded Salura with another Coldain Insignia ring, this one golden.  Salura wondered how many of these trivial tasks and almost useless ring upgrades she would have to do before Garadain really trusted her.<br><br>The next task was to find Tain in the wilderness and help him defeat a band of Frost Giants led by Ghrek.  The twins found Tain easily enough.  The poor dwarf was badly wounded and nearly frozen to death.  From Tain’s description of the Giant’s attack, Salura knew she needed more than her bother’s help to successfully kill the giants.<br><br>Salura put out a call for assistance from the guild and Ranwolff, Elenaya, and Mekenaras came to aid the twins.  Salura was also able to contact her long time friend and hunting ally Rhyanna who gladly came to help out.<br><br>When the giants arrived to finish of Tain, they were met with a fierce surprise. The group in a flash of blades, flying fists and sizzling mana defeated the band in a few minutes.  Salura found an elixir on Ghrek while cutting off his head, and gave the elixir to Tain, hoping it would restore him.  <br><br>The group members, having finished the task, set off again on their separate ways, to each their own adventures.  The twins and Rhyanna returned to Garadain’s camp and presented Garadain the head of Ghrek as proof of the deed.  Yet again, Garadain upgraded the Coldain Insignia ring, this time platinum, and asked if the twins would consider yet another task for the Coldain.<br><br>This task was to find the Orc messenger, kill him and take the message he was to carry to his commanders instead to the Coldain Lookout.  Rhyanna quickly found the messenger and directed Salura to it.  Salura buried the messenger in the snow and tucked his message inside her pack as they headed back to the camp.<br><br>Back at the camp the lookout was alarmed to read the invasion was already on its way.  In fact, Salura and Rhyanna had only beaten the invading rocs by a few seconds.  As the lookout sounded the alarm, Salura located and engaged the leader Scarbrow Ga’Hruk, while Salur healed the battling dwarves and allies, and Rhyanna rooted the Orcs so the dwarves we not overrun.<br>The snow ran red with the blood of the invading Orcs, several dwarves were injured, but none more seriously than a few wounds that would serve well for campfire and bar stories for generations to come.  Scarbrow and his Orcs had been defeated.  Salura presented Garadain the head of Scarbrow and was again given another Coldain Insignia ring of obsidian.<br><br>Salura left Garadain’s camp, promising to return again soon and help with the rest of his tasks.  Salur was glad to return to the Dulak Harbor, where the twins and Rhyanna warmed up by the docks before heading into the luggald caves in search of the elusive Enraged Soulstealer.<br><br>After a few hours of hunting the Soulstealer’s lair, the Soulstealer himself finally showed his ugly face and the trio quickly sent him back to Innoruuk with a message from the twins-we’re coming for you soon.  Salur sent the Soulstealer’s weapon, the soulstripper, to Naram to sell in the bazaar.  The fine weapon added several thousand platinum pieces to the Clan and Rhyanna’s pockets in a few short days.<br><br>“Salur, how’s your smithing arm?” Salura asked slyly.<br><br>“Fine as it ever was, although it may be getting a little weak from lack of use.” Salur laughed as he flexed his arm and showed of his muscled arm.<br><br>“How would you like to get back in front of the Neriak forge again?” Salura asked her brother, already knowing his answer would be an enthusiastic yes.<br><br>“If I heard you right, you said Neriak forge?  I’d love to get back there.  I’m not done making you some new armor.”<br><br>“Good, let me collect some components and some money and then I’ll send you back to make a lot of armor, enough for eight of the Clan.  You, Me, Noril, Eari, Fluf, Basmaati, Damdara and Radwen can all use some of the armor I want you to make.”<br><br>With that, Salura turned and located the nearest Broken Skull Dock Guardian and cast engulfing darkness upon him, as she set about her routine to separate her foe from his money and his life for the good of the Clan coffers.<br><br><br>To Be contineued...<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Baroness Salura Ater'Mors<br>Lady Reaver (Shadow Knight) of Innoruuk<br>Lvl 61<br>The Rathe Server</td></tr>
